<HEAD>Premadasa Meets With Tamil Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> and four members of his Cabinet met for the first time Thursday with Tamil rebels fighting for an independent nation and discussed ways to end the insurgency, officials said. Also Thursday, officials said <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> will help the top Sinhalese militant leader go abroad for medical treatment, a move which may pave the way for peace negotiations with the extremists. The Tamil rebellion and the resulting Sinhalese backlash have claimed more than 12,500 lives since 1983 and unleashed a wave of terror, bombings and assassinations on this once-peaceful island nation. Officials refused to reveal details of the meeting with the Tamils, which concluded for the day after a few hours. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> had received and approved a request from <PERSON> Rohana </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>, leader of the underground <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, to allow him to go abroad for medical treatment. <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>, 46, is believed to have suffered a heart attack recently. The front is an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group which has been at the forefront of the anti-government campaign launched in 1987 to protest peace overtures made to Tamil rebels. The request from <LOCATION> Wijeweera </LOCATION> was made through <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuttal </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> correspondent in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nuttal </PERSON> said he received two telephone calls from a front member on Thursday, who said the group would be willing to hold talks with the government if <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON> was allowed to receive medical treatment in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The request was conveyed to the government, he said. A government statement said <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> had not directly been in touch with the front. The front last month rejected <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s offer of amnesty and seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> if they gave up their campaign of assassinations and calling crippling industrial strikes. An estimated 3,500 people have been killed in the campaign. The peace offer was accepted by Tamil rebels, and a five-member team is currently holding talks with the government. Tamil insurgents launched a bloody rebellion in 1983 for an independent nation in the northern and eastern regions of the country, where most Tamils live. An attempt by <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s predecessor, <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>, to end the rebellion by granting limited autonomy to the Tamils ended in failure after the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, the largest rebel militia, rejected the plan after a brief acceptance. The peace plan, signed in July 1987, also sparked a backlash among nationalist Sinhalese, who said it gave too many concessions to the Tamil minority. The plan was sponsored by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> peacekeeping troops were later despatched to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to enforce an arms surrender by the Tamils. At least 800 Indian soldiers have been killed in hit-and-run attacks by the rebels since then. The Hindu Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of the country's 16 million people, say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese majority in jobs and education. Sinhalese Buddhists make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and the military.
</TEXT>
