<HEAD>U.S. Dependents Moving To Bases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-14, `Emil Kirberg...,' with 10 grafs to UPDATE
with quotes. Pick up 15th pvs, `The plan...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> diplomatic and military families headed Thursday to temporary haven on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases to avoid possible harassment by Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s government. `` The problem is regime-directed gangs,'' such as the group that assaulted opposition presidential candidate <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> and his two running mates on Wednesday, said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said there had been no direct threats against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel, but that in the past the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> government has publicized the neighborhoods where Americans live. <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said he did not know if that was just propaganda, `` but the people around Wednesday were out of control.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> announced that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic dependents would be moved to bases after the assault on <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> and his two vice presidential candidates Wednesday. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> anounced Thursday that <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is being recalled, that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel would be reduced and that both military and diplomatic dependents would be moved either to safe housing or out of the country. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains 10 military installations in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, which is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military headquarters for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. About 10,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers are stationed in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Thursday he was sending 2,000 more `` to protect the lives of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens.'' <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said 105 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens work for the embassy, and the moving order affected 57 spouses and 85 children. The order does not affect 21,300 American civilians not connected with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, many of them retired. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said his daughters are away at college. He was planning to put up three families in his three spare bedrooms at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clayton </LOCATION>, 10 miles from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I've been in the service, or with the service, 25 years,'' said <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON>, a civilian <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> employee. `` We take care of our own.'' The <PERSON> Kirberg </PERSON> family was one of the three <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON> was expecting. They arrived at sunset, unloaded their suitcases in a few minutes and looked at their new surroundings. They said they'd had no trouble but they'd rather be safe. `` The Panamanians have always been friendly,'' said <PERSON> Emil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirberg </PERSON>, who works for <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON>. His wife, <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>, said she had been surprised by the call. `` It was worse last year and we never had a problem,'' she said. The <PERSON> Kirbergs </PERSON> said they put as much as they could into a few suitcases and left their dog with friends. `` I tried to take things that meant something to me,'' said <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>. That included some pillows and a small chandelier. Once inside the gate, <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON> said his wife had sped out to rent some videos. `` I hope she gets some good ones,'' he said. `` I do n't know how long this is going to go on.'' The plan under which diplomatic dependents were moving Thursday was designed for temporary security, and embassy spokeswoman <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said it was not known how <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decisions would affect the immediate situation. <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said: `` Everybody lives in a high-rise apartment building for security reasons. People ca n't see that you've moved, as they could if you lived in a house. `` It's not like the Joads moving from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. You just pack a suitcase for four or five days, get in your car and drive across town.'' All was calm Wednesday in one of the exclusive high-rise neighborhoods where many diplomatic families live. Almost the only vehicle moving in the hot afternoon sun was a beer truck making a restaurant delivery. Some people with pets were boarding them out, <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said, but others planned to return home during the day `` to feed pets or pick up clean underwear.'' Panamanian employees of the embassy were concerned both about harassment and whether they would have jobs if the size of the staff was reduced. `` We can do with very few Americans here and that will probably create more work, rather than less, for the Panamanians,'' the spokesman said. He said the military officials were in a more difficult situation because they had more dependents to deal with. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said there are 10,600 military dependents in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, 972 of whom live off base. Southern Command was operating under condition `` Charlie,'' meaning <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel can go into public areas of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> only on official business and in civilian clothes. <PERSON> Kneebone </PERSON> said his family was in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because the current government had sent him a letter ordering him to leave the country. `` Since we do n't recognize that government, we opened the envelope, photocopied it, resealed it and stamped ` Returned Unopened' on it,'' he said. He said he sent his family home because he thought the expulsion order, and his refusal to obey it, made him a target <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies doing business in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> also should withdraw dependents. Among the larger companies with operations here are <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Colgate </ORGANIZATION>. A person who answered the telephone at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> said the chamber could not express an opinion or give information because `` this is a political matter now.''
