<HEAD>Kissinger Predicts Close Bush-Thatcher Relationship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> will have as close or closer a political relationship with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> than with his predecessor <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> predicted. The former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secretary of state made the remarks Wednesday night in an interview with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s closest allies during his two-term presidency, is due to hold talks with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> when he visits <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for two days starting May 31 during a European tour. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> said: `` The relationship, good as it was between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, will be at least as good, if not better, between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>.'' `` Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> based his relationships very much on personal intuition. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a man who is more reflective about the conceptual matters,'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> added.
