<FIRST>r i PM-Shcherbitsky     05-11 0947</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shcherbitsky,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brezhnev Man in Politburo Bends _ a Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> man on the Politburo bends enough under the pressure of reform to stay in power, but <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> has not budged from his deepest convictions. He was named Ukranian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader 17 years ago to crack down on nationalism in the industrial and agricultural heartland of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. And he indicates nationalism is still one of his primary concerns. `` Nationalist ideas exist everywhere, but we can not allow people who stick to such absurdities to join perestroika,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. At 71, <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> is the oldest of the 12 men on the ruling Politburo and considered one of the most conservative. Except for reformist President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself, he is the only one left dating back to the late Soviet President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON>, a Ukranian, also is the only party leader of a republic <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has not replaced since becoming general secretary in 1985. Reformers complain that <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> is preventing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s changes from taking root in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, a republic with a population of 50 million. But <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> made clear in written responses to questions submitted by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that he feels the earth moving under his feet. `` One can see signs of renewal with the naked eye,'' he wrote. His aides said they could not recall <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> ever responding to a foreign journalist's request for an interview. The Ukrainian leader refused, however, to take any follow-up questions, either in writing or in person. Shcherbitsky is blamed by some for covering up the radiation damage done by the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant explosion, for restraining the local press and for arrests and harassment of dissidents whose political activities would be considered routine in the other European republics of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He denied the charges. `` Some groups attempt to use glasnost and the public rostrum for alien propaganda, national egoism and even anti-Sovietism,'' he said. <PERSON> Schcherbitsky </PERSON> concedes the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> is suffering from accumulated problems such as severe pollution. He said he responds to public opinion these days and, as evidence, he pointed to the scrapping of several nuclear power projects and a dam. In recent months, <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> has come under new pressures for change: <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has begun public criticism of the Ukrainian leadership, and several new reform groups have drawn thousands of people to public meetings. Six of his aides were defeated in their bids for additional positions of power in the recent election, the first in which citizens voted in large numbers against the establishment. `` I have to admit I have never run such an active and intensive election campaign,'' <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> wrote of his successful bid for a seat in the new Soviet parliament. He got 74 percent of the vote in the <LOCATION> Dnepropetrovsk </LOCATION> area, his old power base. The other 26 percent crossed his name off the ballot since there was no alternative candidate. Nine years ago, <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> smashed the <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> human rights group in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> by arresting everyone who joined. Today those activists are out of prison, and some campaigned for his defeat in the election. Some spent a few weeks in jail for their efforts. The grassroots organizations have drawn thousands of people to meetings on ecology, expanded use of the Ukrainian language, legalization of the Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and exposing the crimes of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. Many of them, <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> said, do n't understand that `` we need time, technology and money to make changes.'' He opposes the most general reform group, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, accusing its leaders of ambition and nationalism that `` leads the way to permissiveness and national antagonism, contradicting the interests of perestroika.'' Though none of the major reform groups in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> is openly calling for independence, that is a growing source of conflict in several smaller areas of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Most recently, 20 Soviet Georgians died in unrest after troops broke up a pro-independence demonstration April 9. Ukrainian activist <PERSON> Oles </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevchenko </PERSON> says <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> remains in power because <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> needs him to clamp down on nationalism in the second most populous republic and because <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> voted for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to become the Soviet leader in 1985. <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> confirmed that, `` I supported the election of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeevich </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as general secretary.'' <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> said he has no `` principal disagreements'' with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, despite `` creative discussions'' in <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> meetings. `` A lively, friendly atmosphere has replaced artificial unanimity, and that is a clear and eloquent sign of the times,'' he wrote. <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> sprinkled his comments with references to perestroika, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform program. He insisted the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> is pressing ahead with farm leasing, glasnost and competitive elections, all keystones of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s plan. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is more blunt in his criticism of the Ukrainian leadership's performance. In a March party meeting, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> complained that billions of rubles poured into agriculture have been wasted. A 320 percent increase in investment in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> has bought only a 39 percent rise in output in two decades, he said. But <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> denied Soviet news reports that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> ordered <LOCATION> Ukrainian </LOCATION> party leaders to pay more attention to democratization and to work with progressive Ukrainian writers pressing for reform. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> never raised this question,'' <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> said. He did acknowledge, however, that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief `` expressed some critical remarks and offered advice, which we are considering.'' <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> refused to comment on his reputation as a conservative opponent of domestic reforms, but emphasized that changes must be carefully monitored. `` After all, perestroika is harmed by sluggishness and stomping in one place, as well as by impulsive jumps and overreactions,'' he wrote.
