<HEAD>Families Live on Nerves In Shelters During Barrages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For two months, residents of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> have spent much of their lives in bunkers and basements because of fierce artillery battles between Christians and Moslems. Here is a report on 10 hours in the life of one Moslem family.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Munaymneh family and their neighbors tumbled into the underground shelter in their apartment block when a 155mm howitzer shell exploded in the street, signaling another round of fierce artillery battles in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` This is only the beginning,'' moaned <PERSON> Soumayya </PERSON> <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON>, 35, as she shepherded her two sons, <PERSON> Amer </PERSON>, 12, and <PERSON> Samer </PERSON>, 14, down the stairs on Tuesday. `` Will it ever stop?'' Most of the six families have spent most of the last two months cooped up in the makeshift 33-foot-by-19-foot shelter in the basement of the six-story block in the <LOCATION> Bourj </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Abu-Haidar </LOCATION> district of Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The fierce artillery, rocket and tank battles that have raged between army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mainly Christian forces and an alliance of Syrian soldiers and Moslem Druse militiamen have reached an intensity unprecedented in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war. Some days, as many as 25,000 shells and rockets are fired by both sides. Mrs. <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> clutched two bottles of drinking water. Her husband, <PERSON> Rafik </PERSON>, and the boys carried chairs, blankets and mattresses. `` Do n't forget anything, because we wo n't be able to come up and get it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> told the boys. Life for Christians and Moslems alike has become an endless cycle of waiting out the bombardments huddled in stuffy shelters or basement parking lots, then foraging for food and water or patching up their damaged homes and businesses during the lulls, nervously listening for the first thud of shellfire that heralds another barrage. There were 18 people in the shelter. They slipped into the routine of life underground while exploding shells and artillery guns thundered above them. The men lighted kerosene lanterns and huddled to talk politics. The women spread out mattresses in the `` sleeping corner'' and food supplies in the part of the shelter Mrs. <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> called `` the dining room'' _ the area around a small cooker used to fix tea or coffee or to heat canned food. The children played cards. But everyone was tense as the explosions shook the shelter. The Munaymnehs, who are Sunni Moslems, have missed much of the recent shelling because, like thousands of other Beirutis, they fled the city. <PERSON> Rafik </PERSON> <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON>, a 52-year-old shipping agent, took his family to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. He brought them back to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on April 30, one day after <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> foreign ministers called for a cease-fire in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` We thought it was over after the Arabs announced the cease-fire, and we came back because the kids' school said it was resuming classes,'' <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> said. `` Obviously, it was the wrong decision,'' he said. As the shells exploded, the children argued about the caliber and direction of the rounds. `` That's an outgoing tank shell,'' <PERSON> Samer </PERSON> said when a particularly loud blast thundered above. `` I bet it's that tank on the corner.'' <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> grumbled: `` That tank's inviting trouble. The Christians will start shooting at it.'' A few minutes later five arillery rounds hit the neighborhood, one near the entrance to the apartment building. `` Oh Allah, have mercy on us!'' one of the 10 women yelled. The children screamed. `` Silence! Silence!'' <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> shouted. `` We're all OK. Thank God, the shell did n't damage the shelter,'' he said. His wife and some of the other women recited verses from the Koran, Islam's holy book. The whispered prayers were drowned out by a flurry of news flashes on the half-dozen transistor radios, all tuned to different Christian and Moslem stations, reporting on which districts were getting pounded by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s U.S.-made howitzers. The radios, the families' only link to the outside world, are kept on all the time. `` Is anyone talking about a new cease-fire?'' one of the women asked, her voice trembling. No one bothered to answer her. There have been dozens of cease-fires in the last two months. None lasted very long. The intensity of the barrage eased around midnight and <PERSON> Najwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Quoraitem </PERSON> ran up to her family's third-floor apartment to bring down some manakeesh _ Lebanese pizza made with thyme. `` You have to eat to survive _ that is, if the shells do n't get us,'' she murmured as she passed out the manakeesh. Another woman served tea. The barrage eased near dawn and the children fell asleep. The men took turns to go upstairs to check their apartments. `` The building next door took several direct hits,'' <PERSON> Munaymneh </PERSON> said when he came back. `` Some people were wounded. We'll find out exactly what happened later.'' At daybreak, the families left the shelter to return to their apartments. No one knew when the shelling would resume, only that it would. The Munaymnehs packed and headed back to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>. Their neighbors prepared to spend another night underground.
</TEXT>
