<HEAD>Radar Balloon Damaged, Deflated by Swirling `Dust Devil'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An $ 18 million Aerostat radar balloon operated by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was damaged and deflated by swirling winds Wednesday while it was moored close to the ground, officials said. The helium-filled balloon, equipped with sophisticated look-down radar as an airborne deterrent to drug-smuggling, was struck by a dust devil, a mini-cyclone or miniature tornado, around 1:30 p.m., said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, a Customs spokesman in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said there were no injuries and there was no damage to other property at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huachuca </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> base in southeastern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> where the balloon is tethered. Damages to the Aerostat have not been assessed yet. The Aerostat is 245 feet long, 72 feet in diameter and its hull is made of high-tech materials including Mylar and Tedlar. It weighs about 12,750 pounds, including the radar package of about 3,500 pounds, Customs officials have said. The Aerostat at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huachuca </LOCATION> was the first of a series being deployed along the U.S.-Mexico border. <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said one other Aerostat is in operation at <LOCATION> Deming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, with another scheduled to go into operation at <LOCATION> Yuma </LOCATION>, `` hopefully next month.'' <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said the Aerostat at <LOCATION> Deming </LOCATION> has an overlapping range over the area covered by the damaged device. That, combined with military radar, Customs airborne and ground radar and air traffic control radar will make up for that on the downed balloon. Customs officials have said the balloon has been instrumental in successful tracking of several small aircraft carrying narcotics being smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. But critics have labeled the balloon a white elephant.
