<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     05-11 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jalalabad Quiet after Weeks of Siege, Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The government flew Western reporters to <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> for their first visit to the city since a guerrilla siege began March 7. Here is a report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JALALABAD, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army says it has driven guerrillas away from <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, ending a nine-week siege, and on Wednesday the shelling had stopped in the 16th century city of gardens built by the Moguls. Children played in open spaces bright with lilacs. Afghan soldiers advanced up to 25 miles along two fronts in an offensive begun Sunday against Moslem insurgents surrounding the city, their commanders said. `` As you can see, <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is alive,'' said Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Manok </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangall </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> council </ORGANIZATION> and governor of <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> province. Leaders of the mujahedeen, the `` holy warriors'' who have fought for more than a decade, denied army claims of ending the siege, retaking the Samarkhel garrison and controlling half the road to the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> border town of <LOCATION> Torkham </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammadi </PERSON>, defense minister of the guerrillas' exile government, told reporters in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>: `` It's a total lie.. baseless propaganda The siege of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> continues. <PERSON> Samarkhel </PERSON> continues to be in the hands of mujahedeen, who also control the <LOCATION> Jalalabad-Torkham </LOCATION> road.'' President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government flew 13 Western journalists to <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> to prove it controls the strategic provincial capital 75 miles east of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, once known for magnificent gardens, orchards and palaces, has been under guerrilla siege since March 7. Military officials said the city, 45 miles from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, had been pounded by 131,000 rockets and artillery and mortar shells. It lies near the Khyber Pass astride the trade routes to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, dominating the entrances to the <LOCATION> Laghman </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION> valleys. The modern city was built in the 16th century by <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON>, grandson of <PERSON> Babur </PERSON>, who founded the Mogul empire of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Army officials said at least 523 civilians had been killed and 3,000 wounded during the siege. They said most of the casualties occurred in the first weeks of the first major guerrilla offensive since Soviet military forces completed their withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Feb. 15. Doctors at <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> said nearly all the casualties were caused by rockets or shells. `` We do n't even have one patient with a bullet injury,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Hafizullah </PERSON>, director of the 260-bed hospital. Commanders of the guerrillas, who began fighting after a communist coup in April 1978, had predicted at the onset of their offensive that <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> would fall within days. They had hoped to set up their interim government in the city as a basis for international recognition as an alternative to <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> The rebels are based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and receive much of their support from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Reports from both sides have said <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> was in ruins, with nearly all the mud-and-brick buildings damaged or destroyed and the remaining residents hiding in ditches or basements. The scene in the dusty, rutted streets Wednesday suggested otherwise. Most buildings had been damaged by shellfire, but remained standing. Although shops generally were boarded shut, the city had electricity, running water and working telephones. Farmers worked in fields on the outskirts, harvesting their wheat and planting rice. Lilacs and wild flowers were in bloom and the city had an abundance of palm trees and small orchards. Children played in the sun and their elders moved about the city on bicycles and in horse-drawn carts, sharing the road with tanks, military jeeps and armored personnel carriers. Some neighborhoods were like ghost towns, however. More than 64,000 people lived in <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> when the civil war began, but many fled to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> or to refugee camps in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. No count of how many remain is available, but some said they will never leave, despite hardship and war. `` What would we do? Where would we go? asked <PERSON> Bhargar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a 70-year-old doctor living in a Sikh temple. He said rockets had hit it five times, killing 24 people and wounding at least 100. Early in the battle for <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, the army surrendered key garrisons around the city and the guerrillas came within about six miles of the airport, which was hit by thousands of rockets. The runway was damaged, a cargo building leveled and the windows of the control tower knocked out. `` If it's necessary, planes can land, but I do n't remember when the last one landed,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Jehangi </PERSON>, 42, the airport commander. Military officials have not said how many soldiers have been deployed in and around <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, but estimates run as high as 30,000. Nearly double that number of guerrillas were believed to surround the city at one time. When Soviet troops left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after nine years of involvement in the war, there were predictions that <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s conscript army would collapse Col. Gen. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Delawar </PERSON>, army commander for the area, said of guerrilla claims of quick victory in <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> and the long siege that followed: `` There's an old Afghan proverb. When a man digs a well, he usually falls in.''
</TEXT>
