<SECOND>AM-Welfare,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Foundation Urges Changes In Social Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, saying the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> social welfare system is out of date, has recommended comprehensive changes that include treatment on demand for drug and alcohol problems. The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> report, entitled `` The Common Good: Social Welfare and the American Future,'' concedes that many of its recommendations face uphill political and monetary battles. The report was scheduled for release Thursday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. Details were reported in Thursday editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. The Times said the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> proposals would cost $ 29 billion beyond the $ 500 billion the federal government spends on social programs. The report recommended a tremendous expansion of the Head Start program to reach 900,000 more 3 - and 4-year-olds, and that the government pay for long-term care for the elderly The proposals would also cost the private sector an estimated $ 10 billion for employers to extend health insurance coverage for workers. The panel recommended paying for the additional programs by taxing Social Security benefits. Such a tax would raise more than half of the $ 29 billion annual cost of the recommended programs, the report said. The $ 3 million study was prepared by an 11-member panel of business, civic, labor and civil rights leaders and educators. `` We are on the right track calling attention to the country's social deficit,'' said <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, chairman of the panel and former chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> `` We know we have a hell of a fight ahead arousing people to do what needs to be done.'' One of the most ambitious proposals advocated by the panel is to provide drug and alcohol treatment `` on demand'' at an estimated $ 1 billion per year. It also called for expanding a food program, Women, Infants and Children, which now reaches half of the 6.5 million to 7.5 million people who are eligible.
