<FIRST>r w PM-SteelImports     05-11 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Study Enlivens Debate Over Steel Import Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> study helps document the claim by a manufacturers' group that steel import quotas have harmed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, the group says. The <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> said in a report Wednesday that steel import restraints have reduced American export sales by raising steel prices. The 96-page report by the independent government agency was certain to enliven the debate over whether the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> should continue steel quota agreements with 19 nations and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration negotiated five-year, product-by-product voluntary restraint agreements, or `` VRAs,'' in 1984 with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and other nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has pledged to continue the restraints in some form beyond their Sept. 30 expiration date. But with the steel industry newly profitable, opponents of the curbs believe they can make a case for ending the program, or at least narrowing its scope. The <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> said in the report that the curbs caused steel prices in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to rise by as much as 0.6 percent in 1985, 1.6 percent in 1986, 1.4 percent in 1987 and 0.2 percent in 1988. It said the weakening of the dollar overseas and other factors also contributed significantly to further price hikes. As a result of the VRA-induced price increases, the commission estimated American exports in steel-consuming industries decreased by $ 258 million in 1985, $ 673 million in 1986, $ 699 million in 1987 and $ 95 million in 1988. `` It makes no sense to renew a program that causes such harm to American competitiveness,'' particularly when the steel industry is healthy, said <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenson </PERSON>, spokesman for a coalition of more than 300 manufacturers opposed to the import curbs' extension. Applauding the report's conclusions, <PERSON> Jenson </PERSON> said American manufacturers have been `` hamstrung'' by higher steel prices. The report said recent steel price hikes `` have been distributed unevenly among categories of customers.'' Price increases were not as great for large steel purchasers as for small ones, apparently because the larger purchasers buy a great deal of their steel through long-term contracts with prices set in advance, the <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> said. The question of whether the restraints have caused steel price increases has divided American manufacturers. Last month, a coalition of 374 manufacturers led by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Maytag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and others was formed to lobby for continuing the quota agreements on grounds that the curbs have helped make the steel industry healthier. That coalition contends steel price increases have been caused by strong worldwide demand and shifting exchange rates. The <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> cautioned the figures reflected an `` upward bias'' because of the procedures it used. That means the effect of the import restraints on prices might have been overstated. The study was conducted at the request of the House Ways and Means subcommittee on trade.
