<HEAD>Witnesses Say Thousands Exploited, Forced Into Underground Existence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Immigration reforms have created a `` vulnerable underclass living in the shadows of our communities,'' immigration rights activists told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel. Thousands of undocumented aliens who do not qualify for amnesty are `` being forced into a fearful underground and impoverished existence,'' said <PERSON> Muriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Heiberger </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigrant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refugee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advocacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>. The Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986 act allowed undocumented aliens who could show they entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before 1982 to apply for amnesty and prohibited employers from hiring undocumented aliens. But witnesses told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on immigration, refugees and international law the law has left many harshly exploited and with nowhere to turn. `` As the undocumented are forced further underground, the immigration law is creating everything it was supposed to eliminate _ a vulnerable underclass, living in the shadows of our communities, facing increased poverty and exploitation,'' Ms. <PERSON> Heiberger </PERSON> testified. Unscrupulous employers `` often exploit undocumented workers fearful of reporting subminimum wages, sexual harassment and unsafe working conditions,'' she said. <PERSON> Muzaffar </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chishti </PERSON>, director of the Immigration Project for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ladies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the law has had a deep impact on the so-called `` sweatshop sector.'' Employers are `` finding it easier to exploit these workers and further depress wages and working conditions,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON> countered that those who do n't qualify for amnesty do not have to remain in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON> said the law was not intended `` to benefit the most recent arrivals. ... The law is doing what it intended to do'' by keeping undocumented aliens out of the work force. <PERSON> Cecilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raza </ORGANIZATION> testified that spouses and children of legalized family members have had deportation proceedings initiated against them in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> and elsewhere. <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON> called that charge `` ridiculous.''
