<HEAD>International Writers' Group Accepts Russian, Lithuanian Chapters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAASTRICHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty-five years after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> first tried to gain membership, the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> international writers' association has accepted a Russian and a Lithuanian chapter. Members of the 10,000-strong PEN, whose charter speaks out strongly against censorship, voted unanimously Wednesday to admit the two groups. `` We have at last obtained something we have been fighting for for decades ... the great Russian literature with its great traditions ... is finally among us,'' said the group's international secretary, <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON> The association also criticized <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and seven other nations for imprisoning literary figures and journalists, including a founder of the Charter 77 Czechoslovak human rights group, playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>. Soviet participation has been an issue ever since PEN _ Poets, Playwrights, Editors, Essayists and Novelists _ turned down an application by the Soviet state in 1924, three years after <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> was founded. PEN had kept out the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> because of its persecution of writers and other intellectuals, and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had regarded the authors' group as anti-communist. The approval of the two chapters in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> clears the way for the opening of up to four more PEN chapters there, including <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> and Estonian chapters operating in exile, said <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION>'s outgoing chairman, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. In a speech made before the vote, Soviet novelist <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> told delegates that `` all worthy writers can become members of our PEN center, including those living outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' `` We want our country to have its literature, regardless of the writer's place of residence, regardless of his beliefs and ideas,'' <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> said. `` Thirty years of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s tyranny, 20 years of -LRB- <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s incompetent rule is long enough to ruin any society, particularly a society that has no democratic traditions,'' <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> said. PEN leadership and Soviet authorities agreed the new chapter would operate independently of the official Soviet Writers' Union. Soviet poet <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Bitov </PERSON> conceded `` there ca n't be any guarantee'' that the Soviet PEN chapters wo n't be suppressed or taken over by authorities. But <PERSON> Bitov </PERSON> added: `` There's a kind of belief that everything's been going in a progressive way,'' referring to President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or increased openness, which has been credited for more freedom in intellectual pursuits PEN criticized <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> for jailing at least 24 dissident intellectuals and banning two novels, including <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s `` Tropic of Capricorn. PEN also called on <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> to release <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, who in February was sentenced to nine months in prison. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> had been involved in a demonstration to commemorate the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of his country.
