<HEAD>Exxon Envisions Gradual Buildup Of Cleanup Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> vowed to put 1,600 more workers on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s shores, but said it would take up to six weeks to get them to the front lines of the nation's worst oil spill. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s promise came Wednesday after the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> ordered it to expand its cleanup. State and federal officials have repeatedly criticized <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> for moving too slowly to clean up the March 24 spill. An Exxon spokesman said the number of shore-based workers would reach 5,000 by late June. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said the buildup had to be gradual to provide training and housing. `` You've got to house all these people, you've got feed these people, you've got to train them,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that despite the increased manpower he considers it almost impossible for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to clean all the oil from more than 300 miles of shoreline by its Sept. 15 target date. As part of its cleanup plan, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> also has requested that some environmental laws be waived so it can burn off the oily wastes and process oily water at the Valdez treatment plant normally used by oil companies to clean bilge water from their tankers. Both options were scorned at a hearing Wednesday night. Speakers expressed concern about air pollution from the burning, and said the terminal plant was inadequate for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s needs. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> expects to collect more than 55,000 tons of contaminated material, from tainted water to soiled clothing worn by cleanup workers. `` I feel the people of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, the people of <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> and the people of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> have given their fair share of blood in this situation,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Winchester </PERSON>, a local environmentalist. `` I think you boys ought to go home and work this through again.'' Earlier, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> ordered <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to beef up its cleanup operation and provide federal officials with weekly, detailed operations schedules of cleanup work outside <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION>, where the Exxon Valdez tanker ran aground and spilled its load. The order, announced in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> by Vice Adm. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, was the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s official response to the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> cleanup plan submitted May 1 for <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> approval. The oil, spreading steadily, has fouled beaches along <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s coast as far south as <LOCATION> Wide </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, about 450 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> Authorities said Wednesday they also discovered oil patches on the west coast of <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The crippled tanker is being repaired at Naked Island in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> plans to move the 987-foot vessel to <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> next month. The hull was ripped open by the crash and there are huge boulders inside the cargo hold, scooped up as the craft scraped against the reef, said <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s on-site commander of the spill cleanup. He said it appeared doubtful that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> could meet its Sept. 15 cleanup deadline. `` I am seriously concerned that the investment of resources you describe will not be able to clean the 300-plus miles of shoreline in the time alloted,'' <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> general manager <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, the company's ranking executive in the spill zone. Workers, meanwhile, toiled on the four islands hardest hit by the spill in the sound, hoping to clean the shores a few days before seals begin their annual birthing cycle about May 20. There are about 10,000 seals in the sound, and between 25 and 50 percent may have been in areas affected by the spill, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigman </PERSON>, a biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Game. No seal deaths have been attributed directly to the spill, although biologists say they have seen heavily oiled seals. As of Tuesday, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said there had been 613 confirmed sea otter deaths and 9,918 bird kills.
