<HEAD>House Panel Chairman Says Acid Rain Bill Would Unfairly Burden Nine
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A House panel chairman, demonstrating that the acid rain debate will again pit blocks of states against one other, says proposed legislation to cut sulfur dioxide emissions would place an unfair burden on nine states. Rep. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s energy and power subcommittee, wrote President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday that the nine states account for 52 percent of sulfur dioxide emissions, considered the leading cause of acid rain. But <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said three congressional proposals introduced so far would require the nine to achieve 77 percent of the nation's required reductions The affected states are <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Sharp, D-Ind., wrote <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> because the administration is developing its own acid rain proposals, which could be submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this month `` Nine states in the nation should not be cleaning up both their own and somebody else's portion of the national reduction,'' <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the letter. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said the proposed legislation would emphasize reduction of sulfur dioxide emitted from older, coal-fired electric power plants rather than from industrial facilities. The nine states, because of their geography, use coal-fired plants largely because they do not have access to hydro-power and natural gas, <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said. `` A pound of sulfur dioxide, removed from the air, is of equal benefit to the environment whether it is removed from a small industrial facility in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or a large power plant in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>,'' the letter said. In the past, the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, the primary victim of acid rain, sought immediate action while Midwestern states feared controls on their coal-fired plants would boost electric bills. States that produce large amounts of high-sulfur coal _ <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> _ worried that controls would cause massive job losses in the coal industry. The West, where low-sulfur coal is mined and acid rain is a less serious problem, has been reluctant to pay the cost for new controls. Acid rain is formed when sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide are converted in the atmosphere into acids, which travel far from their starting points to pollute lakes and forests and, according to health experts, cause serious respiratory problems for asthmatics, children and the elderly. The leading sources of sulfur dioxide are coal-burning power plants and industrial facilities. Nitrogen oxides are emitted in approximately equal amounts for asthmatics, children and the elderly.
</TEXT>
