<HEAD>NBC Vows to Run `Roe Vs. Wade' Without Ads, If Necessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Armed with reviews from TV critics praising the made-for-TV movie `` Roe Vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> is asking advertisers to stand up to pressure groups seeking to block the film about the case that legalized abortion. In a May 8 letter to advertisers, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> vowed to air the movie as scheduled Monday without advertising if advertisers pull out. `` I'm not writing this letter to simply sell commercial time,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> wrote. `` We will underwrite this project without support, if necessary. We're very proud of ` Roe Vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>.''' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said the status of advertising time sold during the two-hour film was still unsettled and probably would be until the broadcast date. The fact-based movie stars <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> as a character based on <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> McCorvey </PERSON>, the then-anonymous `` <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>'' plaintiff who sued <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attorney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wade </ORGANIZATION> in the case that went to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON> plays attorney <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Weddington </PERSON>. The abortion battle heightened when the high court heard arguments April 26 in a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case that could affect the 1973 decision. The movie is about the pro-choice advocates who prevailed in 1973, but also portrays sympathetically the prosecutors who argued the other side, though they get much less attention. `` This is discriminatory programming against an entire class of people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willke </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is clearly strong pro-abortion propaganda. There is absolutely no claim that can be made that this is balanced, not remotely.'' He said his group was calling on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> affiliates to refuse to show the movie, or provide anti-abortion groups with at least 30 minutes of time to refute the views they believe the movie represents. In an unusual move, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> allowed advertisers to screen the film before deciding whether to sponsor it. `` A few have withdrawn. Others have been added,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON>. `` We have n't identified any of the names of advertisers in or out and expect it will be fully sponsored. The next couple of days are going to be crucial.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s letter quoted favorable reviews of the movie and said advertisers should be concerned about threats of boycotts as a way for pressure groups to control program content. `` <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> firmly believes the decision about where your messages appear rests with you and your marketing people _ not with those who have a predisposition to judge a program's merits based on their own agenda and no information,'' said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s letter. NBC News' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> will anchor a 30-minute special later in the evening to discuss abortion, but <PERSON> Willke </PERSON> was n't impressed. `` Baloney,'' he said. `` They are controlling the discussion.'' In his letter, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> referred to recent cases of advertisers pulling out of TV programs because of pressure from groups and individuals who find them offensive. He mentioned no specifics, but shows that have been targeted recently include <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>'s raunchy sitcom `` Married ... With Children'' and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s cuttingly satirical `` Saturday Night Live.'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> recently canceled two `` reality-based'' specials, `` Crimes of Passion II'' and `` Scandals II'' due to lack of advertiser support because of their expected lurid content. Both were sequels to previous specials that garnered good ratings.
