touring the city from the bed of a pickup truck. When the pickup was halted by a police blockade it was surrounded by a group of men wearing `` Dignity Battalion'' T-shirts and waving iron bars, baseball bats and rubber hoses. `` By this action <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has demonstrated his contempt for the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people,'' said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> at a news conference. The government, in television broadcasts, accused the opposition of trying to set the stage for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention. Government television showed footage of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, of a CIA-inspired coup in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, and of the coup that toppled President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. The opposition rejects <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s accusations that it is trying to help the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> violate the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties, which cede the canal to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> by the year 2000. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> began its campaign to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> after he orchestrated President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s ouster. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> had tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> after the general was indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug-trafficking charges in February 1988. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> denies the drug charges.
