<HEAD>Sky Sniper Placed on Probation Hours Before Wife's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man charged with killing his ex-wife with an assault rifle then going on a three-hour aerial rampage _ buzzing buildings and firing at cars _ had been placed on probation just hours before the shooting. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, 42, had been convicted Tuesday of assault and battery and of violating a protective order stemming from a New Year's Eve fight with his wife over which television station to watch. She had first asked for a restraining order in January 1988. The couple's six-year marriage ended in divorce four months later. Salem District Court Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> placed <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> on one year's probation. The trouble began later that evening when police in <LOCATION> Danvers </LOCATION>, about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, responded to a domestic dispute call. They found the body of <PERSON> Elvira </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, 30, in her apartment, shot several times with an AK-47 assault rifle, state Trooper <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said the couple's 5-year-old son saw his father kill his mother. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> fled, stole a car from a restaurant in nearby <LOCATION> Peabody </LOCATION> and then commandeered a <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> airplane, which he flew helter-skelter over a 60-mile area of <LOCATION> Greater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, dive-bombing buildings and firing the automatic rifle, police said. He was captured when he landed at <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> early Wednesday, was charged with murder and armed robbery and ordered held without bail for 20 days' psychiatric observation. Before the assault and battery conviction, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> had pleaded guilty in 1979 to assaulting a group of people with a machete and was sentenced to one year's probation. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> told police the group had tried to rob him. The machete incident did not show up in the probation papers given to the judge before Tuesday's sentencing, <ORGANIZATION> Essex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. `` I'm not sure that the outcome would have been any different,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. A court-appointed pychiatrist, Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> told him during an examination Wednesday that he had been treated for psychiatric problems at a Veteran's <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and was taking a minor tranquilizer, Lorazepam, for anxiety. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> served in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Police today were piecing together <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s flight from hundreds of witnesses' reports. Stockbroker <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was walking to a tavern when he heard popping noises from the sky and spotted a low-flying plane. `` About two seconds later, several shell casings landed all around. At that point I realized that the guy was shooting out of his plane,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. During the flight, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> dipped under a bridge, veered within 50 feet of motorists and buildings and fired at targets including parked cars and the Prudential tower's 50th floor skywalk. Police in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> received more than 200 calls about shots being fired. In suburban <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, police said two cars were hit in a shower of gunfire believed to have come from the plane. <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION> air traffic controllers twice evacuated the tower. They said <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> buzzed them repeatedly, forcing officials to close the airport for an hour and reroute late