<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Miners at four southwestern copper mines ended a six-day strike today and returned to work after winning 30 percent pay increases plus higher bonuses, a Solidarity spokesman said. In another development, Solidarity called on the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> to investigate the planting of an eavesdropping device in one of its campaign offices after local officials refused to look into the matter. Preparatory work to reopen the mines began with the first shift, following the acceptance of the agreement by workers on Wednesday night, said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugalski </PERSON> of Solidarity, a member of the strike committee. Normal work at the mines was to start in the afternoon, he said. The strike which began May 5 and involved up to 20,000 miners had been the first major instance of labor unrest since the April 5 signing of a broad agreement between Communist authorities and the Solidarity-led opposition. The agreement led to the reinstatement of Solidarity after a seven-year ban and a government promise to allow the opposition to run for one-third of the seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s lower house and all the seats in its new <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The June elections are to be the first open balloting in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. The free trade union movement said the strike was inspired by the official <ORGANIZATION> OPZZ </ORGANIZATION> unions but joined by Solidarity members frustrated by high inflation, which has reached an 80 percent annual rate this year. <PERSON> Sugalski </PERSON> said the miners won a 30 percent increase in basic wages plus a 30 percent bonus if production goals are met. They originally demanded a 50 percent increase in basic pay. The increase in basic wages averages about $ 1.40 a day, he said. The miners now earn $ 112 to $ 169 a month. `` Solidarity helped miners win pay for the period of the strike, and we are very happy about it,'' said <PERSON> Sugalski </PERSON>. The agreement also calls for `` urgent changes'' in the pay system, he said. Miners have long complained that the pay structure undervalues labor performed during the normal five-day work week, forcing miners to work weekends to make ends meet. The strikes were at four mines near the city of <LOCATION> Lubin </LOCATION>, about 200 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. The official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the strike reduced output by 100,000 tons of ore daily. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is the world's eighth-largest producer of refined copper. In 1987, it exported to the West more than 161,000 tons, worth about $ 233 million. Solidarity workers found the electronic eavesdropping device in campaign offices in the northern provincial capital of <LOCATION> Slupsk </LOCATION>, union spokesman said <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Moskwa </PERSON> said Wednesday. Hew told a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> news conference that the device was found Tuesday in a wall in the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> office the city about 50 miles east of the port of <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. Government spokesman <PERSON> Pawel </PERSON> <PERSON> Byra </PERSON> said he knew nothing about it. `` The <LOCATION> Slupsk </LOCATION> case sheds a clear and worrying light on methods applied by the coalition-government side in the election campaign. It was proved again that the Polish state is still an instrument of a political monopoly,'' said a statement released by Solidarity's national citizens committee The committee is coordinating the free trade union movement's campaign for June's partially democratic elections <PERSON> Moskwa </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Slupsk </LOCATION> committee asked the local prosecutor's office to investigate, but it refused The national committee then complained in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the police.
