<HEAD>Gherman Gets Stiff Sentence in Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A financial planner who bilked clients of millions of dollars was sentenced to 30 years in prison and ordered to pay $ 12.9 million in restitution. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON> on Wednesday on seven embezzlement and mail fraud convictions. <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> said the reason for the stiff sentence was because there were many victims, `` real people, not large institutions,'' who lost money as a result of <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON>'s fraud. `` As the fraud unveiled, he took almost $ 5 million of these people's money,'' <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> said. `` To this day, vast amounts of money remained unaccounted for.'' Many of the dozens of clients bilked were doctors and nurses who entrusted <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON> with their pension plans. They believe he swindled some $ 20 million since starting his `` one-stop shopping'' investment and financial planning firm in 1970. <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON>, charged with misusing $ 10 million of his clients' money, claimed that most of it was wiped out by the 1987 stock market crash `` I never schemed, I never planned it,'' <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON> told the judge. `` I never set out to do this. I never converted other people's money to my own benefit or that of my family. He showed no reaction as the sentence was read. <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON>'s relatives, including his wife of 33 years and their two daughters, were in tears <PERSON> Gherman </PERSON> was arrested last October in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and was returned to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> by federal marshals Dec. 28.
