<HEAD>Opposition Groups Reject Party Offer For Round-Table Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's leading opposition groups have rejected the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to negotiate the details of a transition to a multiparty system, opposition spokesmen said today. The party's governing <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> proposed earlier this week that procedures for next year's promised multiparty elections and other reforms take place in a round-table setting. But the opposition spokesmen said the leaders of eight groups met Wednesday night and decided they wanted to present their views as a single entity. The Communists have demonstrated increasing willingness to share power with other political groups following a severe economic crisis and demand for greater democracy. The Central Committee said the negotiations could be conducted in a setting similar to the series of meetings held recently in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where the government agreed April 5 to reinstate the outlawed trade union Solidarity and allow opposition participation in parliamentary elections. <PERSON> Balint </PERSON> <PERSON> Magyar </PERSON> of the League of Free Democrats said the opposition groups want a two-sided negotiating table and a broader agenda. `` We do not want to negotiate on concrete issues but on the political rules of the game,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> said the talks would have to include a new law on political parties and a new constitution as well as the reforms needed before the June 1990 vote, which is to give voters a choice of parties for the first time in 40 years. According to the daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemzet </ORGANIZATION> and a communique distributed by the state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION>, the opposition groups called on the Communist leadership to make a new proposal within 48 hours. <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATI