<HEAD>Attorneys Criticize Plan Requiring Drug Offenders to Name Suppliers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 County judges have enacted a policy requiring drug offenders to name their suppliers or face additional time in jail for contempt. Some defense attorneys say the measure is unconstitutional. `` Forced and coerced information is suspect, unreliable and potentially dangerous. It raises serious constitutional questions,'' said <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Moncier </PERSON>. The policy violates the Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination `` because it could indirectly be used to produce additional charges against the defendant,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>, another defense attorney. <LOCATION> Knox </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s three <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judges adopted the measure Friday at the suggestion of <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, chairman of the area's <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> At least one judge said he would use the policy immediately. In addition, a <ORGANIZATION> Juvenile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge agreed to use the policy, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> said. The policy is modeled after one in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, which is used with juvenile offenders, he said. Under the program, people convicted of drug offenses can be jailed for contempt of court for not naming their suppliers. Anyone who wants to plead guilty in exchange for a lesser sentence will be told of the policy. If the defendant refuses to name the supplier, the judge may reject the plea agreement, said Criminal Court Judge <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>.
