<HEAD>Swirling `Dust Devil' Damages, Deflates Radar Balloon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swirling wind deflated and damaged a mammoth, $ 18 million radar balloon used to detect drug smuggling across the Mexican border, but the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says radar coverage continues. The Aerostat was damaged Wednesday while moored at the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huachuca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> base, said Customs spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>. A dust devil, or mini tornado, struck the helium balloon, which has sophisticated look-down radar, he said. The 6 -LCB- - ton balloon crashed to the ground No one was injured and there was no damage to other property. The extent of damage to the balloon was not immediately known, but <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said, `` Certainly it can function again. I'm pretty sure of that.'' A second Aerostat is at <LOCATION> Deming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, with another scheduled to go into operation at <LOCATION> Yuma </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> next month. The <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plans six over the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> and four over the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Partial overlapping coverage provided by the Aerostat in <LOCATION> Deming </LOCATION> plus radar at military installations, air traffic control sites and Customs ground and airborne stations will help make up for the downed balloon, <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said. The Aerostat, deployed in June, is 245 feet long and 72 feet in diameter with a hull of high-tech, highly resistant, thin materials. The Aerostat was moored close to the ground because of strong wind before the accident, <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said, and there was speculation debris in the dust devil damaged the balloon.
