<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A member of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observer team that visited <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> said today there are `` disturbing parallels'' between <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> before last weekend's election and the voting scheduled for next February in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` Having just returned from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> our reflections are fresh, and the lessons we have drawn have important applicability to develoments in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuette </PERSON> told the privately financed <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> and Fair Elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schuette </PERSON> is president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which, with its Democratic counterpart, sponsored the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> observer team headed by former Presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. The balloting was branded as fraudulent by observers and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. `` Our experience in observing a variety of elections around the world is that the quality and intention of an electoral law is but one element of the critical determinants of whether an election will be free and fair,'' <PERSON> Schuette </PERSON> said. `` The other two points of analysis are the caliber and organization of the opposition and the over-all organization of government.'' `` There are disturbing parallels, too frequent to be considered accidental, between these three elements in the cases of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` My own analysis of the current environment _ and I should note that the Republican institute has just concluded a seminar in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> with opposition parties on the electoral process _ is that sufficient freedom of organization, expression and activity does not currently exist to ensure a free and fair election,'' he said. On Wednesday, an official of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration reserves the right to seek renewed military aid to the Contra rebels if the Sandinista regime holds power by fraudulent means in next year's election. `` If it is perceived that they have stolen the election, then our policy subsequently will reflect that,'' <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> Counselor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> told the conservative-backed <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> and Fair Elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` The wider this perception, then the stronger consensus there will be for an appropriate policy afterward,'' <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said. The official was asked his reaction to the testimony of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, who told the privately funded group on Tuesday he would favor `` significant military aid'' to the Contras if Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> fails to hold free elections as promised. `` I have nothing to add to what was part of the bipartisan accord a couple of months ago, that the administration does reserve the right to ask for such aid in the future if circumstances change,'' <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said. `` That's not part of our present policy, but the administration has not given away its future right to ask for such things if it seems appropriate.'' The bipartisan agreement, reached in the face of congressional resistance to administration requests for immediate military aid to the Contras, calls for continued non-lethal aid only. Asked by former Sen. <PERSON> Gaylord </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, D-Wis., commission co-chairman, what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy would be if a fair election resulted in an Ortega victory, <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> replied: `` I hesitate to prejudge everything we would do I think there is a presumption that if there is a fair election and we accept it as a fair election, that makes a big difference in our attitude toward <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and certainly our policy.'' <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gershman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, a private grant-making organization that receives an appropriation from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, testified that the Nicaraguan election process `` will not work, and indeed will be a farce, if there is not concerted effort by the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents and by others who are concerned about the situation to insist upon fair rules.'' `` So far, the fear is that there have been certain cosmetic steps that have been taken, perhaps to improve the standing of the government in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and elsewhere, but that there has not been any real effort to sit down and establish an agreement,'' <PERSON> Gershman </PERSON> said. `` Unless there is agreement on rules, it will undermine the legitimacy of the whole process.'' Elections are to be held in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> next February under an agreement <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> made with the governments of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala 