<HEAD>Retail Sales Show Lackluster Increase, Evidence of Slowdown in Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales rose by a lackluster 0.4 percent in April, the government said Thursday in a report cited by analysts as evidence that higher interest rates are taking a toll on economic growth. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales climbed to a seasonally adjusted $ 139.9 billion last month after remaining flat in March and falling 0.4 percent in February. `` The last three months' sales were up 5 percent over the same period last year, barely keeping pace with inflation,'' said economist Lawrence A. Hunter of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` Today's report is another clear sign that the economy has slowed far more than most analysts realize.'' Economists had expected a much stronger rebound in April, anticipating a surge of between 1 percent and 2 percent on the strength of higher auto sales. Car-buying did increase for the first time since November _ it was up 1.1 percent following declines of 0.5 percent and 1.8 percent _ but the gain amounted to only about half of what was predicted. Auto sales have been hit particularly hard by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy of pushing up interest rates to fight inflation, as have housing-related items such as hardware, building supplies and furniture. `` What the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> was hoping was to cool off consumer spending while we still had an expansion led by -LRB- business investment -RRB- spending and exports, and it looks like it's going the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> way,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANI