e only 0.1 percent in April after falling 0.9 percent in March. Sales of non-durable goods, meanwhile, rose 0.6 percent following a 0.5 percent rise. Other categories reporting sales increases in April were gasoline stations, 2.2 percent; and food and grocery stores, 0.7 percent. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, an economic consultant in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the rise in gasoline sales is attributable to price increases. Categories posting declines included: building supply and hardware stores, 0.5 percent; furniture stores, 1.2 percent; bars and restaurants, 0.9 percent, and drug stores, 1.6 percent.
