<HEAD>Pyongyang Preparing its Biggest International Gathering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is preparing to stage the largest international gathering ever in that isolated country: a youth festival with an anti-imperialist theme. About 30,000 people from more than 170 countries are expected for the 13th World Festival of Youth and Students on July 1-8 in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, said So Man Sul, chairman of a preparatory committee for the pro-North <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Residents </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. About 20,000 people from 157 countries attended the last festival in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1985, So said. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has not held a major international event since the 35th World Table Tennis Championships in 1979, which brought 900 players from 85 countries to <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had demanded to be a co-host with <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> of the 1988 Summer Olympics. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> offered to let it stage several of the Olympic events, but the offer fell short of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s demands, and it boycotted the Games. So said the youth festival would be the largest international gathering ever held in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> capital since <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was divided at the end of World War II. The festival's theme is `` Anti-imperialist Solidarity and Peace,'' and will include representatives from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The festival, first held in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> in 1947, is a major political, cultural and sports event involving mostly communist and Third World nations. Previous hosts have included <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. Asked about prospects for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s participation, So said: `` We are n't so optimistic.'' <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has invited South Korean radical students to attend in letters sent through the South Korean government. Since April, however, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has refused to accept further <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> letters meant for radical student groups and dissidents. The policy change followed an unauthorized trip to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by a South Korean dissident, the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, for talks on national unification. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> was arrested on his return to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on April 13 on charges of violating a law requiring all <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> to obtain government permission to visit <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The communist nation suspended all dialogue with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to protest <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s arrest. So said sports events at the festival would include the marathon, soccer, basketball, volleyball, table tennis, gymnastics, swimming and diving. All facilities for the festival have been completed in and around the capital of <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, he added, including hotels, stadiums and theater