<HEAD>Senior Cabinet Minister to Resign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 6 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Cabinet minister in charge of largely unsuccessful efforts to draw black leaders into negotiations announced his resignation Thursday. Constitutional Development Minister <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> gave no reason for his decision, announced a week after he made a ground-breaking speech in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> proposing that blacks be given a role in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, in the Cabinet and in the selection of a president. On Wednesday, another senior <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> member and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, announced his resignation, saying he wanted to return to private life. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has overseen the enforcement of press censorship during the 3-year-old state of emergency. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON>, the leader of the governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>, will resign from the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> on July 1. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, the party leader in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, will resign Sept. 6, when a general election is scheduled. There will be at least six vacancies on the 17-member Cabinet when it meets after the election, providing an opportunity for a major overhaul by F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, the favorite to succeed P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> as president. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> unsuccessfully competed against <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> in February for the position of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. Two ministers of agriculture and economic affairs previously announced they would not seek re-election, and the minister of manpower quit after being linked to allegations of financial impropriety. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>'s portfolio as national education minister also probably will be vacant. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON>, 62, joined <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 and has been a close associate of P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> during the president's 11 years in power. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> often was mentioned as a possible successor to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, but political commentators said his chances were hurt by his lack of progress in persuading prominent blacks leader to enter negotiations about power-sharing. Some blacks were deterred by the government's insistence the white minority retain veto power over major decisions made in any new form of government. Other blacks say they will enter negotiations only if jailed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is freed and bans on militant black groups are lifted. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> announced this week that a group of black mayors and town councilors had agreed to begin negotiations on power-sharing. But the 1988 local election that put these officials in office was widely boycotted by blacks, and black leaders of national prominence have shown little interest in the so-called National Forum. Under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s system of apartheid, the 5 million whites control the government, while the 28 million blacks have no role in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and no voice in national affairs.
