<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Secrets     05-11 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Secrets,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Secrets Act Gets Royal Approval Amid Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s new Official Secrets Act got the royal seal of approval Thursday, even though it has been denounced by critics as a government assault on the public's right to know. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government called it an improvement on the original 1911 act, which contained 2,000 different ways of charging someone with revealing official information, however trivial, without authorization. Critics said the new law's major flaw is that it denies officials who leak information about improper or questionable government conduct the defense that they acted in the public interest or that the information has already been published elsewhere. The law received the Royal Assent, a final formality before taking effect later this year. The Home Office said no date has been announced. The 1911 law, hastily passed during a German spy scare, has given <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> the reputation of being one of the most secretive Western democracies. Technically it covered everything from the civil service's tea intake to the fertilizer applied to Buckingham Palace's flowerbeds. Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said the new legislation `` removes from criminal sanction the unauthorized disclosure of large quantities of official information, substantial as well as trivial, including disclosures which might merely embarrass or inconvenience the government of the day.'' Introduced after months of controversy and debate, the new law codifies the government's right to secrecy in six specified areas covering defense, the security services, crime prevention and detection, and international relations. The only automatic offenses will be leaking or publicizing security service bugging, telephone tapping and mail interception. In other cases of unauthorized disclosures by journalists or the 800,000 civil servants, diplomats and defense industry workers who have taken an Official Secrets Act oath, prosecutors will have to prove a `` damaging disclosure'' has been made about a branch of government. The government says that by shifting the burden of proof to the prosecution, it has enhanced civil liberties. It also says the new law is an improvement because the receiver of unauthorized information is no longer liable to prosecution. But critics say that by specifically excluding the `` public interest'' defense, the government has set freedom back. Newspapers say the government will have little difficulty finding expert witnesses such as retired military officers to testify that publication was damaging. `` What of the man who breaks down the door of a stranger's house to save a child from fire?'' asked <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Birt </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION>, writing in the newspaper, The Independent. `` There may well be damage, but what counts are the good consequences of his actions.'' The new law retains the lifetime gag on members of the MI5 and MI6 intelligence agencies, and continues to shield the intelligence services from any parliamentary scrutiny. `` The government has drawn the cloak of secrecy even more tightly around the operations of the security and intelligence services,'' says Article 19, an anti-censorship organization. Since coming to power in 1979, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government has mounted at least 24 prosecutions under the Official Secrets Act, compared with 34 in the previous 68 years. In 1985, a jury acquitted civil servant <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponting </PERSON>, saying he acted in the public interest in exposing a government cover-up surrounding the sinking of an Argentine cruiser in the Falkland Islands War. Under the new law, <PERSON> Ponting </PERSON> likely would have been convicted. Civil libertarians claim freedom of expression has shrunk during the Thatcher era. They cite the government's increasing use of court injunctions to suppress news; its futile three-year battle to ban `` Spycatcher,'' a retired intelligence agent's memoirs; a police raid on <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> studios to seize tapes; an attempt to suppress a TV documentary questioning the government's version of the killing of three <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> terrorist suspects; a ban on broadcast interviews with Irish militants. At a news conference Thursday, Lord <PERSON> Stockton </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> publishers, said he was `` very frightened that every day takes a step closer to tyranny ... the mechanisms of tyranny seem to be inbuilt in our society.'' Labor lawmaker <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON> said he was concerned `` that secrecy is now becoming a kind of a habit of governments and as soon as you have secrecy in government actions, tyranny is an almost inevitable consequence.''
</TEXT>
