<HEAD>Sandinistas' Election Preparations Criticized, Parallels Seen in
Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nominee to be ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government has `` not met what we would consider standards of legitimacy'' in the first phase of preparations for elections next year `` There were in fact no direct negotiations between the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and the internal opposition groups over the content of the reforms that were to be made,'' <PERSON> Luigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON>, director of policy planning for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, testified at a hearing. `` Rather, these were in effect imposed by the Sandinistas,'' <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON> was among final witnesses in three days of hearings by the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on a Free and Fair Election in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, a bipartisan panel supported by private donations that will come up with suggested guidelines for the February balloting. The commission was established by the conservative <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. The commission also heard from <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuette </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which, with its Democratic counterpart, sponsored the Panamanian election observation team headed by former Presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. After observing the elections in that country, <PERSON> Schuette </PERSON> said, `` the lessons we have drawn have important applicability to developments in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' `` Our experience ... is that the quality and intention of an electoral law is but one element of the critical determinants of whether an election will be free and fair,'' he testified. `` The other two points of analysis are the caliber and organization of the opposition and the overall organization of government.'' `` There are disturbing parallels, too frequent to be considered accidental, between these three elements in the cases of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said. He said he had concluded that `` sufficient freedom of organization, expression and activity does not currently exist to ensure a free and fair election'' in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. That view was echoed by <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON>, who said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` very concerned'' that the first stage of preparations for the election `` has in fact not met what we would consider standards of legitimacy.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> appeared to have shown `` a complete unwillingness to open the system further'' when they empowered President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> to name all five members of an electoral commission made up of two Sandinista members, two opposition members and a neutral member. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s naming of a neutral member in reality will make the commission `` an automatic Sandinista rubber stamp,'' <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON> said. He added, however, that he is `` cautiously optimistic'' that the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> may make changes to make the electoral system more palatable. <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON>, former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration ambassador to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and co-chairman of the commission, said that although <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON> is the ambassador-designate to the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> he was testifying in his current <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> capacity. The Nicaraguan elections are to be held under an agreement <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> made with the governments of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>.
