<HEAD>Family Claim Grain Fumes Killed Loved One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foul-smelling gases from two rancid grain piles near a grain elevator caused the death of a 24-year-old pregnant woman who lived nearby, according to a lawsuit filed by her family. <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Oland </PERSON>, who was seven months pregnant, died in September 1987 from an accumulation of fluid in her lungs, according to the lawsuit filed in federal court in <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Oland </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Lidgerwood </LOCATION> less than 200 yards from two huge grain piles maintained by <ORGANIZATION> Harvest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, the lawsuit said. The piles were begun in 1986 after the company's elevator ran out of space. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpinski </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Harvest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, declined comment on the lawsuit Thursday. The grain piles were drenched by rain before they were covered and began to spoil, according to the lawsuit. Residents of <LOCATION> Lidgerwood </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s southeastern corner 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION>, began to complain of the odor in the summer of 1987. Harvest States removed most of the grain later that year. The lawsuit maintains the odor from the spoiling grain caused medical complications that led to the death of Mrs. <PERSON> Oland </PERSON> and her fetus, according to <PERSON> Galen </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaa </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moorhead </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, attorney representing the family. Storing grain outdoors and using chemicals to cut spoilage is `` an abnormally dangerous business activity,'' said the lawsuit, filed by Mrs. <PERSON> Oland </PERSON>'s father, husband and surviving son.
