<HEAD>Bush Ordering Troops To Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines urgent series, edits and updates with military units,
deletes older military information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today decided to order up to 3,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and evacuate some American dependents from that volatile country, informed sources said. He urged allied nations to condemn Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> for election fraud. Adminstration sources said the Pentagon was preparing to sending the troops from two bases, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ord </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. The sources said one group of about 1,000 would be dispatched immediately from the 7th Light Infantry Division from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ord </LOCATION>. The other, he said, would be drawn from the 5th Infantry Divsion at Fork Polk and would not arrive in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> `` for days'' because that is a mechanized infantry division and the men and their equipment will be transported by ship. The actions would beef up the 10,000-strong <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troop strength in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> with additional forces as one of a series of actions in response to the nullification of the Panamanian election results by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the post-election violent attacks against opposition politicians, said the sources who had knowledge of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision. In addition, some of the dependents of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> were to be returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> while others were being relocated for safety reasons from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and other locations to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, a source said. Further, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was continuing talks with leaders of Latin countries to support various intiatives they were undertaking in the aftermath of what many condemned as an election blatantly rigged by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, officials said. For example, the president backed the call by <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> for an urgent meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, the sources said. `` The president is going to take a whole series of actions,'' said one administration official who spoke on condition of anonymity. The official characterized the moves as `` prudent measures to asure the safety of Americans and assuare the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can fulfill its commitment to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties.'' Earlier today, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had ordered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces to prepare for possible deployment, as he weighed a series of options against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where rioters attacked opposition leaders. `` Our miltary forces that are involved are being readied for any possible changes in their status,'' White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said in describing the administration stance a day after Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> nullified elections that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials condemned as fraudulent. `` We have an obligation to the safety and security of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and we have substantial military commitments in that country. We intend to meet our obligations.'' `` There are also steps to be taken on the diplomatic front,'' he sid. The spokesman would not elaborate on <LOC