condition was stable and there were no neurological complications. Soldiers did not interfere during the beatings, which broke out after troops halted an opposition demonstration to protest what international observers have called the government's theft of Sunday's vote. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and other officials said one of <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>'s bodyguards was killed and about 20 demonstrators injured. The military said four soldiers were wounded. Opponents had hoped to rally international opinion against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and prevent the proclamation of his hand-picked candidate, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Duque </PERSON>, as president. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> asked the 152 dependents of diplomats to move to military bases, and embassy spokeswoman <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said the move was under way. `` You have these dignity battallions moving around town and targeting people. We're not sure who they're next targets are going to be. So rather than leave people exposed to possible attacks by these roving mobs, they're moving people onto the bases just as a precaution,'' she said. At the Pentagon, officials said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had not issued similar orders affecting dependents of servicemen. There are about 14,000 military dependents in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, of whom about 3,100 live away from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases. Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> planned to announce he was sending additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to back up the 10,000 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers already in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PER