<PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> told the newspaper. `` I've got a teen-age boy.'' On the same day <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>'s comments were published in the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, he told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>, `` The victims were homosexuals. They were out in the homosexual area picking up teen-age boys. Had they not been out there trying to spread AIDS around, they'd still be alive today.'' The charges against <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> also state that when people who had read the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> report and heard an <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> radio network broadcast called <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>'s office to complain, they were referred to an attorney's office and told to `` have a gay Christmas.'' The commission alleges the court officials' response was `` cavalier, disdainful and undignified.'' The commission announced in February its decision to initiate formal proceedings against <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> will report to the 11-member commission, then the panel could dismiss the complaint, issue a public censure or recommend the judge's removal.
