<HEAD>Researchers Stymied on Pig Deaths, Could It Be Drought Related?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers have been struggling for more than a year trying to find what malady is killing baby pigs, and one veterinarian says he believes the deaths may be drought-related. Pathologist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> veterinary diagnostic laboratory said the failure of laboratory tissue studies to indicate a culprit is a strong point in favor of his theory the deaths are related to bad feed. It is possible the deaths come from poor quality grain containing toxins being fed to the pigs' mothers, he said. `` The dollar cost goes into the millions. It's a tremendous cost,'' said <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>. He said the number of deaths has increased with the drought and with the related decline in quality and rise in contamination of grain. The outbreak in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> has been in isolated pockets, not widespread, and no figures for the number of pig deaths was available. Others believe a virus or a new strain of disease is to blame. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> said that while researchers have been unable to pinpoint the cause of the deaths for more than a year, `` This is not something to panic about.'' <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> has been studying a mysterious outbreak of baby pigs in <LOCATION> Wabash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, where hundreds of pigs are reported to have died on a dozen farms. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Wollen </PERSON>, a veterinarian-pathologist at <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said a new stra