<FIRST>r a AM-NASAAmes'50th     05-11 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Ames' 50th,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Ames Research Center Marks 50 Years of Achievements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOFFETT FIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty years ago, long before satellites, space shuttles and planetary probes, work began on a national research center that would help make all those things possible. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> is celebrating its first half-century, beginning with an aerial photograph Friday of 2,000 employees arranged into a giant `` 50.'' Over the years, thousands of top scientists and engineers have worked at <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION>, developing swept-wing planes and supersonic flight, contributing to the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo programs and tracking Pioneer's voyages through the solar system. They have searched for the chemical building blocks of life, experimented with plants, insects and eggs in space, studied the effects of weightlessness and looked for holes in the atmosphere's ozone layer `` The two prominent features of Ames have been outstanding people and the development of major, unique, national aerospace facilities,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballhaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of the $ 500 million-a-year center. Space exploration was hardly a hot topic in 1939, when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION>, predecessor of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, founded <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, named for <ORGANIZATION> NACA </ORGANIZATION> chairmen <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON>. When tensions mounted before World War II, the government's <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> lab in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> was seen as vulnerable to attack by <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and a second facility was proposed 3,000 miles away at the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Moffett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> base, 45 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> The threat from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was considered, but the site also had low-density air traffic, good flying weather, adequate electricity and access to the growing western aircraft industry, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>. Today, <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> is in the heart of high-tech <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, and has grown into a maze of dozens of laboratories, wind tunnels and offices. `` When I first started working here -LRB- in 1971 -RRB-, during lunchtime I'd wander around in the various wind tunnels and laboratories and ask people what they were doing,'' <PERSON> Ballhaus </PERSON> said. `` It's fascinating, like a technical Disneyland. The Flight Research Building was put into operation in August 1940. By the fall, three wind tunnels were under construction to work on problems of theoretical aerodynamics. When the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> entered World War II, the basic research <ORGANIZATION> NACA </ORGANIZATION> emphasized was phased out while labs concentrated on immediate problems. Research on deicing airplane wings had started at <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION> as early as 1927. But the problem was licked at <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION> in 1944, proving the effectiveness of the new laboratory. In 1952, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a specialist in high-speed theoretical aerodynamics, was working on missile research when he developed the `` blunt-body theory,'' which would later solve the problem of heating during a spacecraft's reentry into the atmosphere. That theory would shape Project Mercury's reentry capsule and play a key role in the design of the Gemini and Apollo crafts and their heat shields. Ames work on high-speed flight helped lead to Capt. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeager </PERSON>'s first supersonic flight in the Bell X-1 on October 14, 1947. Eight years later <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION> researcher <PERSON> R.T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> came up with the `` supersonic area rule,'' which minimized drag on supersonic craft and allowed still faster planes. In 1958, <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> invented the lifting body, wingless craft able to fly back into the atmosphere from space, survive entry heating and land. That idea eventually led to the space shuttle. <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> was given responsibility for basic research in life sciences in 1961 and began studying the chemical evolution of life. In the 1970s, <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> broke new scientific ground with its Pioneer series of space probe. Pioneer 10, launched in 1972, became the first craft to go through the asteroid belt and returned the first close-up pictures of Jupiter. Four years later, the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence began at <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION>, a program that listens for radio signals from other civilizations. `` Ames has had a big impact on the space program and on other sciences and it still is very important,'' said <PERSON> Ballhaus </PERSON>. `` The work here is helping us understand the universe and our environment.''
</TEXT>
