<HEAD>Voters Asked to Reset Property Tax Bases to Ensure School Survival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON> and legislative leaders are asking voters statewide to approve a property tax formula that opponents say would take control of school financing out of local hands. Supporters say the measure will aid about 100 public school districts with inadequate property tax bases, some dating to the early 1900s. A property tax base is an amount a school district can levy each year without seeking voter approval. Measure 1, on the ballot Tuesday, would reset all districts' tax bases to include whatever extra levies local voters have approved to make ends meet in 1988-89. Under the state constitution, the tax base can automatically increase by up to 6 percent a year. So broadening the base will make for bigger automatic increases each year. Supporters say this change is the next step in getting <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> out of a crisis that had schools closing for lack of money a few years ago. The first step, a `` safety net'' law passed in 1987, allowed schools in danger of shutting down to fall back on the previous year's tax levies without additional voter approval. However, school officials trying to make budgets on 2-year-old tax levies say they do n't have enough money to cope with inflation, enrollment increases and other needs. <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON>, a Democrat, and legislators from both parties argue that Measure 1 will bring some stability to school financing until a new source of funds can be developed. `` This is just a step, as was the safety net, toward equity,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitzhaber </PERSON>. `` There are no losers in this, only degrees of winners.'' Only about a third of the state's 303 school districts are potentially affected by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s ballot proposal. They are mostly rural and relatively small, meaning voters from the large, urban districts are likely to determine the fate of their tax bases. `` It tests whether people view schools as a statewide or local responsibility,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danielson </PERSON>, lobbyist for the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the state's largest teachers union. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Brummell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, a long-time tax critic and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeowners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the issue is whether taxpayers want `` remote voters'' to determine their taxes. `` The main thing we object to in the property tax is it's simply no longer fair,'' he said. `` Until the system is changed, there's no need to go through with this mediocre approach. Passage of Measure 1 automatically would enact a companion bill with $ 112 million in special school aid and property tax relief. It includes $ 35 million for educating handicapped students, $ 35 million for districts with high property tax rates and $ 22 million to ensure no districts get less basic aid under the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s actions this year than they now receive The bill also provides $ 20 million with the aim of limiting homeowner property tax bills for schools to no more than 5 percent of income.
