<HEAD>West German Says Short-Range Nuclear Arms Could be Eliminated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Short-range nuclear arms could be eliminated from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agree on reducing conventional forces, a leading politician in the governing coalition said Thursday. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> seeks East-West negotiations on reductions in the battlefield nuclear weapons, most of which probably would be used on its territory in case of war, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> are opposed. Officials in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> said West German leaders, who have pressed <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> for a more favorable attitude toward reforms in the Soviet bloc, would discuss superpower relations with <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, the Soviet foreign minister. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> met with Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Thursday and is to visit <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> on Friday. About eliminating short-range weapons, <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambsdorff </PERSON> said in a radio interview: `` This is not possible today, but it could be if conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were reduced to levels each side requires for defense.'' <PERSON> Lambsdorff </PERSON> is chairman of the liberal <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, junior partner in Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s coalition. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, also a Free Democrat, have called for speedy East-West negotiations to reduce short-range weapons. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> say the weapons are an essential part of the Western alliance's efense strategy. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Thursday for more talks on the matter with British counterpart, Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>. In a meeting two weeks ago, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was unable to convince <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> to drop his demand for negotiations, which has split the alliance just before a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit scheduled for <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> later in May. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> rejected a proposal by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that the superpowers negotiate reductions in the short-range weapons. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has 88 Lance missile launchers, most of them based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The missiles now have a range of 75 miles, but modernization would increase that to about 250. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> is expected to address many topics during his visit to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, including disarmament and relations between the two countries. He will meet with both <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>. Before meeting with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> will see <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> at a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> officials Friday in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. A federal government source said: `` We expect <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> will be reporting on the current state of Soviet-American relations. This area is very important and interesting for us.'' In remarks to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on April 27, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said the West `` should support reform processes in all <LOCATIO