<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Never mind that the sky was filled with gray clouds. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> Z. Mollusk saw his shadow on Thursday, which means summer will arrive a week early. The hermit crab performs an annual ritual similar in spirit to that of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Punxsutawney </PERSON> <PERSON> Phil </PERSON>, who is said to herald six more weeks of winter whenever he sees his shadow on Groundhog Day. Tracy French, <LOCATION> Miss </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, carried the crustacean mascot to the beach on a tiny decorated throne. To symbolize <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment to clean beaches, the throne was set upon a container of recyclable materials such as aluminum cans and glass bottles With toddlers performing a hula around him and some devoted fans and curious onlookers standing nearby, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> crept out of his shell and saw his shadow _ or so says <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Soifer </PERSON>, the city's imaginative public relations director `` It was overcast, so no one thought he would see his shadow,'' <PERSON> Soifer </PERSON> said. `` But trust me _ there was an itsy-bitsy, teeny-weeny area of sun that came through.'' <PERSON> Soifer </PERSON> said the omen that summer will arrive a week ahead of its normal June 21 date was authenticated by <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> the Amazing Weather Dog, another <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> mascot. The dachshund also performs an annual ritual. He buries <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> immediately after the event. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, however, was again rescued and returned to his `` heated solarium,'' an aquarium tank in <PERSON> Soifer </PERSON>'s office, until next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elementary school pupils set free 7,000 ladybugs in what their principal called an ecological alternative to an annual balloon launch. Balloons, with notes attached, are often released by school and community groups eager to see how far their messages will travel. Many wind up in fields and wetlands, where the balloons can be fatal to foraging wildlife. The idea to launch ladybugs came from <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> Clift </PERSON>, a school volunteer who works at a gardening shop that sells ladybugs as an alternative to pesticides. <PERSON> Clift </PERSON> said she bought seven 1,000-bug bags and donated them to the school. <ORGANIZATION> Chamberlin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> pupils prepared for the launch by reading about ladybugs and discussing them in class. On Wednesday morning, they took small plastic cupfuls of the bugs into the schoolyard, where the insects flew away or were set on tree trunks or blades of grass. `` I think they're neat because they crawl all over and they're good for everything,'' said <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockwood </PERSON>, 7 `` It's gross. They feel funny,'' said 6-year-old <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dusablon </PERSON>. `` It's a new tradition that we're starting,'' principal <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcotte </PERSON> said. `` It went great. We'll do it again next year.''
