<FIRST>r w AM-Welfare     05-11 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welfare,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Calls for Welfare Overhaul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the nation's welfare system needs a $ 29 billion overhaul to expand the social safety net with services like treatment on demand for drug and alcohol problems and long-term care for the elderly Other recommendations include expanding the Head Start program for 3 and 4 year olds, assuring all pregnant women access to prenatal and well-baby care, raising the minimum wage and requiring welfare recipients to work after receiving benefits for a certain period of time. The foundation's report, `` The Common Good: Social Welfare and the American Future,'' is the result of a three-year, $ 3 million study by a panel of business, civic, labor and civil rights leaders and educators. `` The current social welfare system is out of date and severe gaps in protection and opportunity for millions of Americans remain,'' said <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, panel chairman. The current system `` leaves too many people dependent and vulnerable at critical stages in their lives,'' he said. The panel recommends financing the broad array of additional welfare, education and health care benefits by taxing Social Security benefits that exceed recipients' lifetime contributions. Such a tax would raise more than half the $ 29 billion annual cost of the recommended programs. The federal government now spends $ 500 billion a year on social programs. The report proposes spending $ 6.2 billion in federal support to expand programs such as Women, Infants and Children, Head Start and Medicaid. All pregnant women would have access to prenatal and well-baby clinics and 900,000 more 3 - and 4-year-olds would participate in the Head Start program States and local governments would be encouraged to begin and strengthen programs to combat teen pregnancies, to reduce the high school drop-out rate and coordinate training and youth guidance programs. About $ 1 billion would be spent to provide drug and alcohol treatment on demand. Also, the estimated 37 million uninsured would be covered by health insurance through a blending of employer-based insurance and an expansion of Medicaid. Employers who did not offer a basic package of health insurance to its workers would be required to contribute to a public fund that would finance coverage for those not working and uninsured. The panel's plan would permit unemployed people to receive lump-sum payments so they can relocate to areas of greater employment opportunities, and the minimum wage would be raised to restore the purchasing power of the 1981 level.
</TEXT>
