beyond the .10 mark, and it was not our intention she get that much.'' A person who has a .10 percent blood-alcohol level is considered legally intoxicated in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. A hospital spokeswoman said <PERSON> Offenbacker </PERSON> was treated in the emergency room and released. She returned to work the next day. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said he believes Capt. <PERSON> Lana </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, in charge of training for the police department, should have supervised the program. `` It was an oversight on her part,'' he said. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> bought two cases of beer and two bottles of wine for the five drinking participants at a cost of about $ 23, her expense voucher showed. `` I threw in a bottle of <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION>'s whiskey that I had at home because I do n't drink myself,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. Offenbacker had been drinking the whiskey before she fainted, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` This was the first time we had a training session of this nature and we made some mistakes. I'm not sure we'll have a similar training session again,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said.
