<HEAD>Canada, U.S. Accuse East Bloc of Impeding Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegates to a forum on press freedom accused four East bloc nations Thursday of doing little to further the cause, and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> urged the nations to drop what it called their `` same tired old excuses.'' The 35-nation forum brought together <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and every European country except <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION> to monitor compliance of an accord on improving the information flow between East and West. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian delegations concluded that <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> had shown little progress in fulfilling their commitments to the accord, signed in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in January. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> responded to the charges in its concluding statement at the month-long Information Forum, saying the West was not looking at the full picture. Chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that `` very little progress'' had been made with the four East bloc countries. `` We did n't expect to solve all problems, but I do n't feel we accomplished as much as I'd like to have,'' said the former head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Canadian Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> said in a speech that some nations remain in a dark age, where the only `` correct facts'' were the government's, contacts with foreigners are taboo, and free communication does not exist. `` The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> meeting has, unfortunately, only reinforced our view that such backward practices remain the norm in some Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> countries,'' he said, referring to the four nations. `` When these countries were justly criticized,'' <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> said, `` we were treated to the same tired old arguments'' that criticism was internal interference or deliberately confrontational. The security conference ended in January in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> with agreements committing the 35 signatories to improve the flow of information and improve working conditions for journalists. Czechoslovakian chief delegate <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Spacil </PERSON>, the only one of the four to speak Thursday, said in his concluding statement that `` confrontation or bias or disinformation ... is counterproductive.'' He said his country was undergoing a `` transitory period'' of instituting reform and a `` new system in all spheres'' would come into effect Jan. 1 next year. <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> said the Czechoslovaks had lied about the circumstances of an arrest of a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reporter May 1 during coverage of a dissident protest, saying he had no identity papers despite the fact that they were holding his passport at the time. He and other delegates said reluctance by some <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries to repeat a <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> promise that all the forum's undertakings were binding had kept a final communique from being composed Instead, as called for under the accord, all proposals made at the forum were to be passed to the security conference for consideration. Soviet chief delegate <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyadyshev </PERSON>, a magazine editor, expressed overall satisfaction with the forum, saying it had brought the participants to a `` new level of understanding.'' He refused to comment on criticism of hi