<HEAD>Administration Seeks Retargeting of Training Money to Teens And Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on Thursday proposed rewriting the nation's premier job-training program to target most spending on the unskilled poor and teen-agers and to hinge some federal money on improvements in state training and education efforts. The program was co-authored by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> when he was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The suggested amendments to the Job Training Partnership Act answer most criticisms of the program and are substantially in line with changes proposed by several congressional Democrats, leading Republicans and Democrats alike to predict passage of a revised <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> this year. `` There is an urgent need for more than job training,'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said in outlining the administration proposal to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on employment and productivity. `` Many desperately need basic skills training, literacy and remedial education.'' Although the proposed amendments would significantly redirect the program, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said they are needed because of the changing demographics of the American workforce and not because of major flaws in the initial legislation. `` Its record on advancing the employability of disadvantaged youth and adults, and returning dislocated workers to the economic mainstream has been unprecedented,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` But <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> can be made even better.'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, called <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> `` the singularly important work of this committee during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years.'' But he agreed with Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> that the recession-spawned program needs to be reworked to address current labor shortages, particularly in high-skills fields. The chairman of the subcommittee, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., has introduced a package of similar amendments and expressed confidence minor differences in the approaches would be resolved `` I think we're going to get a good bill out of this committee that we're all going to be able to agree on,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> is by far the nation's largest training program, receiving $ 2.4 billion this year to serve an estimated 1.9 million people. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has requested stable spending for next year. <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the proposed amendments would increase per-person training costs and therefore cause some modest reduction in service levels. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, however, said those reductions likely could be offset if states did a better job of coordinating federal, state and other education, training and counseling programs. Current <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> spending formulas send two-thirds of the money to areas based on their unemployment rates. The amendments would make the concentration of economically disadvantaged the overriding factor in spending decisions. Also, youth training programs now scattered throughout sections of <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> that also deal with adult training would be collected into a separate entity, which Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said would allow dramatic improvements in efforts to curb high youth unemployment, particularly in inner cities. During her testimony, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was flanked by three participants in JTPA-funded programs. They sparked applause from subcommittee members when they discussed their troubled childhoods and achievements made possible by the training and education they were receiving. They also met briefly later with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House. Also among the changes proposed by the administration: _ Rewriting eligibility requirements so that in addition to being economically disadvantaged, all youths and half the adults seeking enrollment in <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> programs would need to have additional barriers to employment such as literacy or basic skills deficiences Teen parents and the homeless also would be given preference. _ Rewriting program guidelines to encourage more thorough training, including deletion of provisions that weigh a program's success by the number of placements it Such provisions have been criticized for encouraging programs to select applicants who already have marketable skills so that they can be placed in jobs quickly. _ Requiring, for the first time, that <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> funding for summer jobs programs go only to youths who are enrolled in an approved education or training program during the school year _ Requiring individual assessments of all prospective trainees and for those accepted into programs, an individually tailored program to meet the distinct education, training and placement needs of each trainee _ Establishing grants for states that set clear goals for their training programs and submit to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans that demonstrate improved coordination between training and related programs
