 A woman facing a manslaughter charge in her baby's cocaine-related death says the case worsened the pain of the `` worst time of my life.'' <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>'s 2-day-old baby, <PERSON> Bianca </PERSON>, died Feb. 4. Authorities blamed the death on prenatal brain damage caused by cocaine use during pregnancy and charged the mother with involuntary manslaughter and delivering a controlled substance to a minor. `` I loved her, I did,'' Ms. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, who had been without legal counsel, accepted an offer of free representation from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> said Thursday in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Winnebago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Logli </PERSON> says he filed the charges in an effort to protect children. But some legal, public-health and medical officials say fear of prosecution could prevent drug-abusing mothers-to-be from seeking help for themselves and their fetuses. Ms. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, 24, refused to discuss the allegations that her drug abuse was responsible for her daughter's death. But her position on what government officials should do in such cases was clear in the interview Wednesday. `` They should help people,'' Ms. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said. `` I tried to get help, but I did n't get any.'' She does not have a telephone and could not be reached to elaborate, but her <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> attorney, <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON>, said most drug-abuse treatment programs will not accept