<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Crisis     05-11 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Crisis,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Response Measured in First Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Faced with his first crisis as president, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has decided on a measured response to the tumultuous situation in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, concerned that more decisive action could imperil longer-term <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests in the area. He said he was sending troops `` to protect the lives of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens.'' But he ordered no direct military action and no new economic sanctions against the government of <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> warned of the consequences of failing to send a `` clear signal'' to the `` enemies of constitutional rule'' in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and elsewhere. But the seven points <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined indicated that if <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is to be overthrown, it will have to be primarily the work of Panamanians and not Americans. The president obviously is hoping that other democratic nations will close ranks against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and that the Panamanian's resulting isolation will encourage him to move on to other pursuits Since Sunday's national election, a number of countries have expressed varying degrees of indignation about the irregularities reported by hundreds of international observers. These countries include <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. And <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is leading a campaign to have the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> take a strong stand for democracy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. If this fails to impress <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, he might still take note of the most controversial step <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced _ the dispatch of 2,000 or more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> combat troops. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> may be concerned that the troops have a more aggressive purpose in mind than the stated one of protecting American lives. It is not unusual for a strong nation to try to achieve political goals by projecting military power without actually using it. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> backed away from a more pugnacious military response out of concern that it could provoke anti-American uprisings in the hemisphere. That approach might have succeeded in ousting <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> but the diplomatic costs would have been exorbitant. Slapping a trade embargo on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> would have made the economy there scream, but the impact would have been felt for years to come _ long after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s departure. So <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is relying on rhetoric and diplomacy to weaken <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, after declaring that the opposition candidate in Sunday's election, <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, won the election, is now calling him `` president-elect.'' It is a tactic aimed at robbing <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> even further of any claim to legitimacy. As for the diplomatic approach, the administration will be lobbying hard over the next few days for a strong resolution at the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers meeting expected to start next Tuesday. Based on the regular <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> permanent council meeting on Wednesday, the prospects are not bright. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryce </PERSON>, delivered a strong attack on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s perceived attempts to steal Sunday's election but only three of the 30 other hemispheric countries joined in the criticism _ <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated that his bag of anti-Noriega reprisals was not exhausted in Thursday's speech. `` We do not rule out,'' he said, `` further steps in the future.''
</TEXT>
