<FIRST>r a AM-MOVEAnniversary     05-11 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MOVE Anniversary,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Years Later, MOVE Catastrophe Is Remembered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Saturday marks the fourth anniversary of the confrontation between the MOVE group and city officials that ended with an airborne police bomb that incinerated an entire block and killed 11 people. Officialdom has spent four years trying to sort out what went wrong. About two dozen lawsuits have been filed against the city and its four top officials at the time of the disaster. The city already has paid about $ 2 million in claims to neighborhood residents for damages to their property. Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> appointed a blue-ribbon investigating commission to report on the man-made disaster. It accused the mayor of gross negligence in his handling of MOVE, a radical group, and called for grand jury indictments in the deaths of the five children. Two grand juries investigated but no one was indicted. On Friday, attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowser </PERSON> will publish `` Let The Bunker Burn: The Final Battle With MOVE,'' a 150-page book which contends the people in the house were executed by their local government and it could happen again. `` I had to write this book,'' said <PERSON> Bowser </PERSON>, who served on a special city commission investigating the disaster. He believes someone should have been indicted for what happened. `` We think there is a deliberate effort to sweep it under the rug,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Meek </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> MOVE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a group sponsoring a memorial service and seminars this weekend on the May, 13, 1985, disaster. `` Many people in the city would like to forget that it happened _ they'd like to pretend that it did n't happen,'' <PERSON> Meek </PERSON> said. `` But it did happen, and it was our government that did it, not some government far away.'' Last December, <PERSON> Meek </PERSON> said, his committee mailed questionnaires to 70 local, state and federal legislators from the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area, asking pointed questions about MOVE and its aftermath. They got three responses. `` I was surprised not to hear from a lot of people,'' he said. `` A veil of silence has been put over this.'' The 1985 confrontation began when police evacuated the block in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, seeking to arrest some members of the radical group at their rowhouse fortress and to evict the others. Police had clashed with MOVE in August 1978, when one police officer died and three police officers and five firefighters were wounded. When police ordered the 1985 eviction, the adult MOVE members refused to come out and kept their children with them, cursing the police through bullhorns and promising to fight them. A state police helicopter finally dropped a satchel on the roof that contained a crudely rigged plastic explosive device. It started the fire that went out of control, destroying the MOVE house and 60 other homes on the block.
</TEXT>
