<HEAD>Iowa Going To Sea Without Repairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The battleship <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, on which 47 sailors died last month in a gun turret explosion, will proceed with its next regular deployment this summer without undergoing repairs, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. But a decision has been made to fix the damage after it returns, a spokesman added. The service, in a brief statement, said the battleship will be departing in June on a scheduled deployment to the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> along with a number of other warships. `` The ship is fully operational except for the No. 2 gun turret, and had already been scheduled to go to the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, Naval Shipyard for post-deployment repairs'' after returning from the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said. Since it will take several months to obtain all the necessary repair parts, `` turret No. 2 will not be repaired prior to deployment.'' `` But it is now the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s intention to repair the turret,'' said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kudla </PERSON>, a spokesman. `` The engineering survey team indicates the damage to the ship was contained in turret No. 2, and all other systems on the ship _ including the engineering plant _ are in excellent condition and fully capable of supporting the upcoming deployment,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> concluded. `` The <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> remains one of the most powerful and durable ships afloat.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced last week the damage to the huge battleship could be repaired for an estimated $ 15 million to $ 20 million. At the time, however, officials declined to say with certainty the turret would be fixed and if so, when. There had been some doubt about repairs because of the vessel's age The <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> was commissioned in 1943 during World War II and no vessel of its type has been built since that war. Forty-seven sailors died on April 19 inside the No. 2 gun turret while loading a 16-inch gun with powder. The huge battleship still has two other turrets, each with three 16-inch guns.
