<HEAD>Superpowers Agree to Cooperate to Fight Oil Spills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker-Soviets, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed Thursday to cooperate in pollution emergencies in northern waters, like the oil spill that has fouled <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s coastline. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> signed the accord on the last day of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s two-day visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It pledges superpower cooperation in combating spills of oil and other pollutants in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chukchi </LOCATION> seas between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. The news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the agreement provides for the development of a `` joint plan of drastic measures'' by the superpowers in the event of a spill. Each country is required to notify the other immediately of a pollution emergency, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials will hold joint exercises on how to fight ocean pollution, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The signing of the agreement is a major step toward developing Soviet-American cooperation in dealing with the consequences of ecological disaster at sea,'' <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalimonov </PERSON>, an official in the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Khalimonov </PERSON> was quoted as saying the cooperation `` will allow specialists to define within hours the scope of an accident, map out joint measures to overcome its consequences and get down immediately to their implementation. Earlier, such procedures took days and sometimes whole weeks.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the cooperation envisaged by the agreement began to function even before <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> signed the formal document. A Soviet ship designed to skim the surface of the sea was hired to help clean up the oil spilled by the Exxon Valdez tanker, which ran aground in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> on March 24. But Exxon officials, who were paying the Soviets $ 15,000 a day for the aid furnished by the Vaidagubsky, said Tuesday the ship was being sent home because it was not designed to handle the hardened, taffy-like mass the spilled oil has created.
