<HEAD>Court: Republication Of No-Longer-True Story Wasn't Libelous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, overturning a $ 2 million jury verdict, ruled Thursday that the reprinting of a newspaper article was not libelous even though the article was no longer true when it was republished. The 1972 article by syndicated columnist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, which reported that the president of a labor union was under federal investigation, was distributed by a rival union during a 1975-1976 battle over which union would represent state workers in <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>. Although <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, was under investigation for alleged mob ties when <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s story originally was published, the investigation ended a few months later with no charges brought against <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>. The jury concluded that <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> 94 of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> had libeled <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> and NAGE by reprinting <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s article without showing that <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> since had been cleared. The jury assessed $ 2 million in compensatory and punitive damages against the council and the parent union. Chief Justice <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, who wrote the high court's unanimous opinion, noted that both reprints included the date of the original article in type `` larger than the text print. `` Aside from the fact that the original article was dated and accurate, the text referred to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> as president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> wrote. `` The majority of the original column was devoted to a discussion of the upcoming 1972 presidential election between <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>. `` These historical references indicate that the reprints referred to prior events and not to matters occurring in 1975 and 1976,'' <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> wrote. The fact that the reprints were published during a `` heated labor-election campaign -LRB- when -RRB- the important constitutional concerns regarding free speech are greatest'' also weighed in the court's finding that they were not libelous, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> wrote. It was the second time the case had been before the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. In 1986, after the original jury had rejected <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>' lawsuit, the justices overturned that verdict and ordered a new trial <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>' lawyer, said he was puzzled by the apparently contradictory opinions. He said he had not decided whether to seek review in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanzler </PERSON>, the attorney representing the <ORGANIZATION> AFSCME </ORGANIZATION> union, said he believed the court overturned the first jury verdict because the trial judge died in middle of the case. `` Frankly, the case should never have gone to the jury because it was determined those articles were true as circulated,'' he said.
