<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The investigation by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Inspector General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> into a federal low-income housing renovation program came under fire Thursday on Capitol Hill from legislators who questioned the conclusions that there was no evidence of criminal wrongdoing. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> was also criticized for waiting until a day before former Secretary of Housing and Urban Development <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> was scheduled to leave the department to interview him and for singling out for culpability <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>, the former assistant secretary for housing who was responsible for administration of the program. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> housing about their roles in the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Section 8 Moderate Rehablitation Program and the subsequent investigation of its selection and allocation process. Two weeks ago, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, the current <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary, suspended more than $ 100 million in fiscal 1989 spending for project under the program. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' investigation had uncovered a system that `` was undocumented, ignored existing standards and regulations, and was based on the perception and reality of favoritism and abuse of non-public information'' through which former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> appointees and other former government officials won lucrative consultanting contracts. `` Why would you have waited ... until Jan 19 of this year to interview the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> who was going out of office the next day?'' queried Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, the subcommittee's chairman, noting that <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' probe had begun almost a year earlir. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said his investigation did not immediately turn up any evidence of <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s possible involvement and he said `` it was just a matter of scheduling interviews.'' But <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> insisted, as he had another hearing earlier this week, that problems existed in the program before he gained his post in October 1986 and spending decisions were `` discretionary'' for Pierce In January 1987, <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> said a selection committee was set up that included himself; <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, former executive assistant to <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>; and an undersecretary for policy. But <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> conceded <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> had final approval over any recommendations made by the group. The <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's investigation cover activities in the program from January 1984 through November 1988. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> also asked why <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> made no `` specific recommendations regarding possible violations of law'' by former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> answered that his office had consulted with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> throughout the investigation and found no evidence laws had been violated. `` I find a disturbing indication in the documents that because these allocation formulas and the laws that pertain to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> are not criminal statutes, that the conspiracies that go on here of individuals working together in order to go around established procedures are treated as if they are not criminal matters,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing the report, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> added. Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass described <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> as `` one of the few people that we could ever talk to at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'' during the previous administration. But <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> later took <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> to task because of his hesitancy to name <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> as the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> official directly responsible for the alleged abuse and mismanagement in the program and he said the inspector general's conclusions might `` compromise'' any future investigation. Rep. <PERSON> Marci </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaptur </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, indicated she might request a special prosecutor to investigate the program.
