<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Elephants     05-11 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Elephants,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenya Urges Ban on Ivory Trade To Save Elephants From Poachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> on Thursday urged an international ban on the trade of ivory in an attempt to curb the illegal slaughter of elephants, which has halved <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s elephant population since the early 1970s. Experts say a dramatic increase in elephant poaching has been spurred by record world prices for ivory. Ivory sells for about $ 91 a pound, and an average tusk weighs 11 pounds. `` The policing of the elephants' survival is not easy, but it will be more practical if any ivory trade is banned,'' <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Katana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngala </PERSON>, minister of tourism and wildlife, said at a news conference. Conservationists believe there are about 750,000 elephants left on the continent. They say poachers are killing about 75,000 of the mammals a year. If the slaughter continues at that rate, the population could be wiped out by the year 2000. An aerial survey last year found an estimated 20,000 elephants in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, which 15 years ago had an elephant population of 121,000. <PERSON> Ngala </PERSON> said the government will conduct another count in June and July. He said <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> submitted its recommendation on a trade ban Thursday to the <LOCATION> Lausanne </LOCATION>, Switzerland-based Convention In Trade Of Endangered Species. If two-thirds of the convention's approximately 100 members vote to list elephants on the convention's Appendix One at the group's next meeting in October, international trade in elephant products would be banned <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s neighbors to the south and east respectively, have submitted similar proposals to the convention, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Leakey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s director of wildlife. However, countries such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, a major ivory consumer, are likely to oppose the proposal. <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, one of the few African nations with a growing elephant population, has annual elephant kills and a thriving legal trade in elephant products. In the last 12 months it has earned about $ 600,000 in legal ivory sales. <PERSON> Ngala </PERSON> said that while <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> realizes some African countries would suffer from an ivory trade ban, such action is crucial if the elephant is to survive. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> also plans to fence parts of its wildlife parks to better protect elephants, <PERSON> Leakey </PERSON> said. Since the beginning of the year, he said, as many as 300 elephants have been killed in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s parks.
</TEXT>
