<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:Cabildo Adv15   05-11 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Cabildo, Adv 15,0899</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Use Mon PMs, May 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>One Year Later: No Restoration Work on Historic Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Cabildo, the building where the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> was signed, stands echoing and vacant, only the 20-foot ceilings and other architectural details hinting at more than 200 years of history. Large chunks of the ceilings and floors are ripped out of one of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' most famous landmarks. Where maps and pictures once hung, stenciled instructions order, `` Repair cracks entire wall'' and `` Remove plaster.'' But there are no workers to follow those instructions, or to replace the third story, destroyed by a fire May 11, 1988, because the state has n't come up with $ 1.2 million to get things ready for renovation. Firefighters rescued most of the Cabildo's treasures, including the death mask of <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>. A temporary roof was installed after the fire, but without a third floor to hold the building together the mortar between the massive gray stones of the front wall lost its grip. The wall had been leaning since at least 1850, but daylight now showed through the corners. Crews installing inch-thick rods to tie the front wall to the back discovered a new problem: asbestos, used in renovations years ago. That prompted the state fire marshal to check not only the Cabildo but other nearby museum buildings and order $ 1.2 million in repairs. Insurance covers $ 4 million in fire damage but not the ordered renovations, so State Museum Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> is looking to the state _ at a time when Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> is trying to cut $ 700 million from the state budget. But <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> is confident he can get the $ 1.2 million. It's not new money, he said, but funds left over from other State Museum capital projects. `` It does n't add to the burden that the Legislature is facing at all. It's money that is there from the past,'' he said. He is worried, though, about cuts proposed by <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who has said all agencies not protected by the state constitution must slash their budgets by one-quarter. `` Those budget cuts are devastating,'' <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> said. `` They'll effectively destroy the State Museum system if they go through the way they've been proposed I do n't want to be the guy who has to lay off 25 people. `` The amount of money involved is n't that big. We're talking about the cultural heritage of this state. It's got to be worth a couple million dollars. `` If it's not, I'm in the wrong business.'' Meanwhile, <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> is asking for $ 2 million in donations to refurbish and improve exhibits in the State Museum buildings near <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. New exhibits, in <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON>'s plans, include getting someone to develop a video game based on the 1815 Battle of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, which actually occurred after the War of 1812 was officially over. `` The visitors will represent the British and have to attack <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s position as it was at the time of the battle. They will discover what the British were up against and will understand why <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> chose that spot and why the British lost.'' Other planned exhibits include plantations, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s early and colonial history and the Cabildo itself, he said. `` One of the problems we have is that so much history took place in the Cabildo that is germane to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that I wish we had twice as much space, because it all deserves telling.'' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> was under Spanish rule when the <ORGANIZATION> Casa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabildo </ORGANIZATION>, or town hall, was built in the 1790s on the site of a police station. Fire had destroyed the roof and woodwork of the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garde </ORGANIZATION> in 1788 and 1794, but its heavy brick walls and floor remained and were incorporated into the much larger Cabildo. After 1803, when the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> doubled the size of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the Cabildo housed the Government of the Territory of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and municipal police station moved in 50 years later. <PERSON> Plessy </PERSON> <PERSON> vs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, the case that established the `` separate but equal'' racial doctrine that stood until 1954, was among the many cases heard there. <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> figures it will take about 18 months to develop the exhibits, but the work ca n't start until the money is in hand. He hopes to reopen the Cabildo in the first half of 1991. The combination of publicity about the Cabildo because of the fire and the new exhibits should boost the number of visitors from about 150,000 a year to about 250,000, he said. When all of the Jackson Square complex is open, he figures the number could be a million. `` As tragic as the Cabildo fire was _ and I do n't ever want to go through anything like that again _ I think in many ways it will be looked upon as one of the best things that happened in the history of the State Museum,'' he said. `` It has forced people to take a second look at something they took for granted, to understand that all of these resources are precious, are special, deserve better care than perhaps they had been given.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs May 15</NOTE>
