<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv14   05-11 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv14,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>National Trust Goal Urban Renewal, not Urban Removal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It sounds like a place of musty closets _ quiet, passive and probably pretty dull. That is not at all what <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> has in mind or on his agenda at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> figures that preserving the past does n't require living in it. So as president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, he is lobbyist, cheerleader and traveling salesman for what he sees as an effort to build <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s past into its future. By his reckoning, the preservation movement is the most active and effective force in rebuilding and reviving <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities in 1989. Urban renewal tore down what was there and tried to replace it with something new. `` The movement,'' as <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> calls it, seeks to revive what is there and put it back to use. He maintains that works better because people prefer to live, shop and work in neighborhoods and places they know, in buildings with a flavor of history about them. Rebuilding, with the emphasis on creating housing and facilities for moderate - and low-income Americans, is only part of `` the movement. It sometimes blocks bulldozers, and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> boasts of a leading role in opposing development of a suburban shopping mall on part of the Civil War battlefield at <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, adjacent to the national park that already protects the main site of the battle. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted late last year to buy the land involved. That and such measures as a 1988 law to protect historic shipwrecks, and scores of traditional projects to guard and maintain historic sites fit one image of the preservationists, as a movement pursuing worthy projects that really do n't have much to do with everyday life. But the same people who fought off the <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> mall are taking lessons from the people who build and run malls, and applying them to the rescue and revival of shopping districts, many of them shuttered for loss of customers to suburban shopping centers and discount houses. The Main Street project provides advice and in some cases support for projects in 30 states, from rural downtowns to old but reviving business districts in cities like <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. Part of the advice is that neighborhood merchants change their old ways and adopt the techniques of the malls such as opening and closing the shops at the same hours, and cooperating on advertising and promotions. The National Trust's programs provide loans and grants that emphasize restoration for more than its own sake, with refurbished buildings providing housing, community centers and commercial space. They do n't add up to a lot of units, but as <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> notes, any dent in the problem helps, especially in the era of the budget crisis. A sampling of buildings that Trust programs have helped preserve: _ A hotel in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>, which now provides housing and a community center for elderly tenants living on low fixed incomes _ An 1874 municipal building in the <LOCATION> Dorchester </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, to be converted into apartments, offices and shops _ A <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> convent, built in 1889, now to become 11 low and moderate income apartments _ A former <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, which is to be rebuilt as low-income housing and a shelter for the homeless The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> has a $ 26 million budget this year, a speck in federal budget terms. Just under a fifth of the money comes from the government, the rest from contributions and the dues of about 220,000 members. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, 48, has headed the national trust for five years, lengthy tenure on the resume of a man who has been a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> lawyer, a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> state official, director of the Office of Government Ethics under two presidents, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. He'll need all of his insider's skills as he lobbies to undo limits on the credits a taxpayer can claim for investing in historic rehabilitation or low-income housing. Without the tax incentive, investment in the restoration of historic buildings has plunged by about 60 percent. Putting it back would cost about $ 200 million a year, and that's not likely to be a popular prospect in the current budget crunch
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 14</NOTE>
