 House tax-writers rejected President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s savings and loan bailout plan, approving an alternative that threatens to swell the federal deficit over the next three years by $ 43 billion to $ 50 billion and possibly force a veto showdown with the White House The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, with 2 of 13 Republicans joining its 23 Democrats, voted 25-11 Wednesday to include the government's full $ 50 billion share of the most massive corporate bailout in history in the fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1991 budgets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> got its foot in the door of <ORGANIZATION> Avon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, offering more than $ 2 billion to buy its larger and more conservative rival in person-to-person sales. Analysts predicted the $ 39-a-share cash offer Wednesday by <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>, known for its sales force's evangelistic attitude, would precipitate a drawn-out battle with Avon, made famous by its genteel `` Avon Lady'' image of years past. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> in partnership with <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> owns 10.3 percent of <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION>'s outstanding common shares, but <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> is not participating in the purchase offer, <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has approved rule changes designed to make the securities industry's arbitration system more fair to disgruntled customers By a 5-0 vote, the commission Wednesday authorized a series of changes, spurred by complaints from unhappy investors who discovered after the October 1987 stock crash that they had signed away their right to sue their brokers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, the driving force behind the insider trading investigation that rocked Wall Street, said he is leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> after four years as its top cop. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, a lanky, soft-spoken 38-year-old attorney who became the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s youngest-ever enforcement director in early 1985, said Wednesday he will step down in mid-July. He said he had no specific plans after that.
