<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     05-11 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top New York Futures Trader Subpoenaed In CFTC Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the most influential players in Wall Street's commodity markets has been subpoenaed in the government probe of possible trading abuses, but he said investigators indicated he is n't a target. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tudor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, whose trading firm manages more than $ 500 million in commodity funds, said Wednesday he was cooperating with the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in its civil investigation of trading practices on four <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> futures exchanges. Another trader, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Effron </PERSON>, has been subpoenaed by a federal grand jury in a criminal investigation headed by <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office into possibly illegal trading practices on the markets, his lawyer said Wednesday. <PERSON> Effron </PERSON> is the first trader to be publicly named as receiving a grand jury subpoena. He reportedly is not a target of the criminal probe. The inquiries are separate from a criminal investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> into allegedly widespread fraudulent trading practices on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest commodity markets. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 34, is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Tudor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which he founded in 1984 and is considered the most prominent among more than 50 traders from whom federal investigators have requested information. The firm also was subpoenaed. The subpoenas, which reportedly were delivered last week, do not imply any wrongdoing. Tudor president <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> issued a statement that <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and the firm `` were among the many traders and firms that received civil subpoenas to provide information in connection with a <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> investigation of others.'' `` Mr. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and Tudor understand that they are not the subject of the investigation,'' he said. <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> would not say whether the government told the firm and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> they were not targets. Market sources, who asked not to be named, also said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> was not a target. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> reportedly is seeking information on <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' dealings with <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Effron </PERSON>, two futures traders who have been mentioned as possible targets. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> inspectors one week ago raided <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s offices at the commodity exchanges as part of a federal grand jury criminal investigation His attorneys have denied any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Effron </PERSON>, 29, has been subpoenaed by the federal grand jury and the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, said his lawyer, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>. `` In the grand jury probe they've indicated he is not a target,'' <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> said, `` and the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> has n't indicated anything.'' Another reported target is <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Semel </PERSON>, who runs a brokerage in gold, silver and other commodities and was fined by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for an alleged trading scheme with <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> in 1985. <PERSON> Semel </PERSON> has refused to comment or provide the name of his attorney. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, whose firm manages money for 15,000 customers, is a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and board member of the <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where he reportedly made most of his money. He also conducts ethics training classes with a former <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> chairman and is highly regarded in the industry. He runs a highly successful publicly offered futures fund, one of what are known as commodity pools, in which a group of futures investors pool funds run by money managers. A person familiar with the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s order of investigation said Wednesday it includes review of possible violations of rules governing commodity pools. Under <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> guidelines, those could include use of customer funds for personal accounts or failing to provide customers with necessary disclosure documents. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> probe also reportedly examines violations that include pre-arranged trading, use of advanced knowledge of customer trades to trade for personal accounts and conducting of trades in order to skirt tax obligations. The government has subpoenaed the <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the Coffee, Sugar and <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> seeking information on brokers. It also has directly subpoenaed at least 26 traders.
</TEXT>
