<HEAD>District's Problems Described as `Quite Insignificant'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The problems remaining at savings and loans in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and four nearby states are insignificant when compared with the troubles besetting the industry nationwide, a federal regulator reports. `` Our members have a stronger position to work from than some other regions,'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moines </ORGANIZATION>, said in the bank's annual report. The Des Moines office oversees thrift institutions in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. The report also said that while overall operations were unprofitable last year for the 176 savings and loans in the district, combined outflows of deposits from those institutions fell more than 25 percent from a year earlier and assets climbed to record heights for a third straight year. It said that with most of the district's previously insolvent thrifts in new, more secure hands this year, there was an improved earnings outlook for 1989. The report was distributed as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wrestled with how to finance the $ 50 billion cash infusion for savings and loan rescues proposed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Unfortunately for our five-state area, the president's plan for resolving the troubles of the nation's thrift industry came after the majority of District Eight insolvencies had been resolved,'' <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> said. `` The remaining problems in the Eighth District look quite insignificant when taken in a national context.'' The <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> district found new owners for 17 insolvent thrifts last year, leaving just eight troubled institutions in the region. Seven of those insolvent thrifts already have been placed under federal conservatorship awaiting completion of congressional action, and the eighth is scheduled for the same attention, said <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Honarmand </PERSON>, a district spokesman. There are four Missouri problem thrifts, two in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> now under the supervision of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. They are <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> and Loan in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Sioux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> and Loan of Cherokee and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estherville </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> and Loan of <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Girardeau </LOCATION> all in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Honarmand </PERSON> said a state-chartered S & amp; L in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, which he would not further identify, would be placed under federal conservatorship later this year. Nationwide, about 350 thrifts are listed as insolvent by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, while another 250 are described as solvent but in need of government help. In 1988, 223 thrifts were closed or rescued across the country. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moines </ORGANIZATION> said 80 percent of its member institutions were profitable last year and improved from their performance of a year earlier. But widening losses at the remaining institutions far offset those gains. Overall, thrifts in the <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> district posted a loss of 92 cents for each $ 100 in assets in 1988, close to the national performance of a loss of 94 cents per $ 100. This widely recognized measure of profitability is called return on average assets. For example, 43 thrifts in the district, representing the top 25 percent, posted what the agency called an `` exceptional'' return on average assets of $ 1.10 for each $ 100. That compared with $ 1 in profit for each $ 100 in assets a year earlier. But the bottom quarter had combined losses of $ 4.06 for each $ 100 in assets in 1988, sharply higher than the overall losses of $ 1.40 for each $ 100 in assets for the same group in 1987. The district regulates 82 thrifts in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, 45 in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 32 in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, 12 in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and 6 in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> said it appeared that consumer confidence has remained fairly stable in the district. Despite the widespread coverage of the crisis in the thrift industry, deposit outflows from member thrifts in the district fell last year. Withdrawals exceeded deposits by $ 1.7 billion overall last year in the district, but that was down from $ 2.3 billion in 1987. And <PERSON> Honarmand </PERSON> said that when accumulated interest earnings were added to the deposits remaining at district thrifts, there was a net increase in deposits of $ 840 million last year. `` Most depositors are loyal to their local institutions and want to continue doing business with them,'' <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> said. `` The bottom line in the thrift industry is public confidence.''
