<HEAD>Bidder Gets Extension for Eastern Offer; America West Ups Shuttle
Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal bankruptcy court extended its bidding deadline for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> for at least one potential suitor, while a bidder for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s lucrative <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> shuttle raised its offer and another airline offered to buy other assets. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> extended Wednesday's 5 p.m. EDT bidding deadline for an investor group led by <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>, a prominent <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> commodities trader, to give it more time to receive financial information from strikebound Eastern. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it would pay a total of $ 751 million for the <LOCATION> Boston-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-Washington </LOCATION> shuttle and 10 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757 airliners, raising by $ 25 million the cash portion of its initial $ 726 million bid. That price also would top a rival $ 365 million offer that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has accepted from developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for the shuttle. In another development, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> rival <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> offered $ 525 million for certain <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> assets, including 15 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757s and related equipment, ground facilities, airport landing slots and three U.S.-Canadian routes. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> said its offer was for spare engines, flight training simulators and other hardware related to the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757s; <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s maintena