TION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, stated it needed more time to discuss with its unions the feasibility of integrating the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workforces and was not prepared to submit a formal bid for Eastern at this time. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has held discussions with officials of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions. Last Friday, he informed the court of his interest in buying <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> airport hub. Former baseball commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, whose $ 464 million deal to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> collapsed in mid-April, was still interested in acquiring the airline, sources close to <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> said Wednesday. However, it was unclear whether he would come forth with a firm new buyout plan, the sources said. Following a recommendation by bankruptcy examiner <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> decided that any bids submitted after Wednesday's deadline would be disqualified except `` for good cause shown. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> granted the two-day extension to <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>'s group because confidential <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> financial data sought by the group was accidentally sent to the wrong person, according to <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s lead bankruptcy attorney. <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> CRT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a futures and options trading company based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. It was not immediately clear under what conditions <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> would accept late bids by others. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> and the principals of the bidding groups did not return phone calls Wednesday seeking comment.
