<HEAD>Mustang Ranch Stock Sale Halted After Marketing Efforts Stall</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Wallstreet one word is cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second attempt to turn <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s best-known house of ill repute into the country's first publicly-owned bordello has stalled after the stock offering fell $ 5 million short of its goal <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wallstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is underwriting the sale, said Wednesday his company had negotiated an extension of the sale of stock in the Mustang Ranch until Oct. 31 to allow time to restructure the offer. In the meantime, the sale of common stock in <LOCATION> Mustang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has been halted and all the money received for the shares so far will be returned to investors, <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON> said in a statement released by his office in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> `` The rules of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ... require that we make this move,'' he said. <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON>, the president of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wallstreet </ORGANIZATION>, was out of the office Wednesday and unavailable for comment. Wednesday was the deadline for the three-month-old bid to take the <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> public through a $ 23.3 million stock offering at $ 20 a share. <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON> said last week about 75 percent of the 1.165 million shares had been sold, leaving the company with a $ 5 million shortfall. <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON>'s statement said an amendment would be filed with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and the states that have approved sale of the stock to reflect the terms of the new deal, which <PERSON> Walloga </PERSON> said would change the types of securities <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> would offer. `` No details of the newly structured offering could be released at this time pending a response from the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to a request for an interpretive ruling concerning a technical issue which arose in developing the amendment to the offering,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> attorney and vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said in the statement he expected the amendment to the registration to be filed with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> by June 15. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> would not comment specifically on the offer, citing <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> rules which forbid parties in a stock offering to discuss them. <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is an investors' group composed primarily of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> businessmen and attorneys who are making a second attempt to turn the brothel public. A 1985 bid by <ORGANIZATION> Strong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, led by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, fell through after failing to generate enough interest in the $ 18 million proposal. The money raised in the current sale was to have provided $ 13 million to buy the 102-room brothel and its 440 acres of land from <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON>, $ 5 million in exchange for the Confortes' promise not to set up a competing brothel and $ 5.3 million for expansion, improvements and working capital <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON> has been trying to sell the brothel 10 miles east of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> since 1985 when he was released from prison after serving 18 months on a tax conviction. He has said he expects most of the money from the sale to go to the federal government in payment of his long-standing tax debt plus the hefty interest and penalties it has run up.
