<HEAD>Shareholder Suits Say Millions in Oxy Money Wasted on Chairman's
Art</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> _ whose art collection includes works by <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> and Impressionists _ is wasting millions of dollars in company funds on `` self-aggrandizing'' plans for a <ORGANIZATION> Hammer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, shareholders charged in two lawsuits The suits, which became public Wednesday in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Chancery Court, seek court orders blocking further <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> spending on the planned museum, requiring return of money already committed and canceling Hammer's employment contract with <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION>. `` Defendant Dr. <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> has breached his duty of loyalty to <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> and its stockholders by instigating and forcing <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> to participate in his personal plan of self-aggrandizement in creating his own personal museum,'' one suit says. The 91-year-old Hammer, who carefully cultivates a media image of international philanthropist and unofficial business envoy to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, will fight the allegations as `` totally without merit,'' a company spokesman said. The lawsuits, filed in the state where the oil-and-chemical giant is incorporated, name both <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> and its directors, including Hammer, as defendants. The actions center on a first-quarter expense of $ 36 million to purchase an annuity to fund the planned museum, on rent-free use of company office space for museum purposes and on a corporate commitment to fund construction of a building for the museum at a cost estimated at $ 30 million to $ 50 million. Requests for a Hammer response were referred to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Kauffman </PERSON>, who represents a special committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> board that approved the museum support. <PERSON> Kauffman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> directors acted well within the law and in keeping with their duty to the corporation in approving charitable spending that would enhance the company's standing in the community. `` All kinds of companies choose to spread their good will in different ways,'' <PERSON> Kauffman </PERSON> said. `` We choose to spread our good will in a way that will benefit hundreds of thousands of people. To say for one minute that this is not going to benefit <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> is, in my opinion, just ridiculous.'' One suit was filed by <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, trustee for the estate of <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Adason </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, which holds 700 <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> shares; the other by <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brody </PERSON>, who describe themselves as <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> shareholders without detailing their holdings. They seek injunctions that, among other things, would bar further <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> support of the museum, including rent-free use of company buildings; cancel compensation to Hammer; and require an accounting of any losses the company incurred in connection with the museum. They also allege that proxy material mailed to shareholders for the company's upcoming annual meeting was misleading about the $ 36 million expenditure for the museum, including it as unallocated corporate expenses. The Sullivan-Brody suit paints a particularly unflattering portrait of <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer in detailing a dispute with the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> over the future of his personal collection, said to be worth $ 250 million to $ 400 million. The collection includes works by Dutch, Flemish, German and Italian masters; Impressionist works and a codex, or book of notes and drawings by <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON>. Last year, Hammer canceled what the museum portrayed as a promise to donate his art to the county when museum officials rejected conditions including posting a full-length portrait of the industrialist at the entrance to the exhibit. Other conditions unacceptable to the museum, according the suit: That the collection be kept intact forever and displayed under Hammer's name; that names of other museum benefactors be removed from galleries displaying <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>'s art; that the collection get a special curator answerable to a Hammer foundation rather than to the museum. The dispute led to <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>'s plan to build his own museum, the suit says, adding: `` Unlike other wealthy collectors, Dr. <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> does not plan to build ` his own museum' with his own ample funds. Rather, Dr. <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> is requiring <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> to provide substantially all the financial support.'' Company attorney <PERSON> Kauffman </PERSON> disputed at least part of that, noting the considerable value of the collection Hammer intended to contribute to the project. Hammer, whose 1987 pay was $ 1.9 million, has held sway over <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> since 1957. Based on contacts he made during a post-World War II medical mercy mission in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he served as unofficial envoy for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government during the Cold War. As relations have thawed in recent years, he has led a parade of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businesses into the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, setting up joint ventures for chemical plants and the like. Hammer, who holds a medical degree, has used his connections and company jet to get American doctors to the scene of various disasters, including the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident and the Armenian earthquake.
