<HEAD>Boyd Jefferies Takes Witness Stand Against Bilzerian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Convicted stock brokerage founder <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> has taken the witness stand for the third time in a federal criminal securities law trial, this time saying he engaged in four unlawful stock deals with <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>. Testifying Wednesday at <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>'s securities fraud trial at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, who said he spoke on the phone often but only met once with the <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> chairman, detailed their dealings in four stock transactions in 1985 and 1986. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> testified that on four occasions either <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> or <ORGANIZATION> Jefferies </ORGANIZATION>' account executive <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Landy </PERSON> asked him to purchase large blocks of stock either for or from <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> to hide the stock's ownership. Then the prosecutor, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, asked <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> if he considered each deal `` lawful or unlawful.'' `` Unlawful,'' <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> said four times. The indictment alleges that <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, who founded the Los Angeles-based brokerage house, <ORGANIZATION> Jefferies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, secretly held stock for <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> in four unsuccessful takeover transactions involving <ORGANIZATION> Cluett </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hammerhill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, H.H. <ORGANIZATION> Robertson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The ruse allegedly was used to help <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> secretly accumulate large stock positions in companies he later would attempt to take over. But on cross examination, defense attorney <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathews </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> if he intended `` to commit any crimes in any transactions with Mr. <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>?'' `` No,'' replied <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, who earlier said he pleaded guilty to two felony counts in a plea bargain with prosecutors. <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, is accused of conspiracy, violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986. If convicted, <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> faces a maximum pealty of five years in jail and a $ 250,000 fine on each count. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, 58, turned government informant in 1987 after he was turned in by convicted stock speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, and has pleaded guilty to two securities-related felonies. He said he faces a maximum 10 years in prison and $ 500,000 in fines although prosecutors are supposed to detail his cooperation to the sentencing judge. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> and his lawyer have said they do n't expect him to serve any prison time. It was the third time <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> has testified for the government in a securities fraud case. He twice took the witness stand in the stock manipulation trial of <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its vice chairman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>. Twice that case ended in a mistrial.
