<HEAD>Plan to Tax Mail-Order Sales Debated on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, No so, to CORRECT no to not; picks up 9th
graf, ``Many of; also moved general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON>, Land's End and L.L. Bean addicts beware _ the nation's governors want you to begin paying sales taxes on your mail-order shopping sprees. Governors, joined by state legislators and mayors, are urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to overturn a 22-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision and require large mail-order companies to collect sales taxes n sales to out-of-state customers. As a result of that ruling, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> told a news conference Wednesday, hometown merchants are at a decided disadvantage and states, cities and counties are losing more than $ 1.5 billion a year in tax revenue. `` Because state sales taxes run from 5 percent to 8 percent of the cost of the goods sold, the unfair tax advantage by out-of-state firms in sales taxes is greater than the average profit margin of Main Street merchants,'' Sinner said. In fact, he added, the average hometown merchant's profit margin is less than 3 percent. Opponents of the proposal held their own news conference to warn that consumers wo n't put up with it. `` This will have the maximum irritation effect on tens of millions of consumers who would have to do the tax calculations every time they order,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levering </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, R-Wis., whose state is home to Land's End, added that the bill `` unfairly targets the elderly, the handicapped, farm families and the millions of consumers who rely on mail-order purchases for many of their basic needs Not so, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which chose to emphasize the bill's effect on well-heeled yuppies: `` Many of the goods sold by mail-order firms are expensive, high-quality, designer-type goods that appeal to young urban professionals: pastel sweaters, $ 24 cotton T-shirts, fancy briefcases, electronic gizmos and exercise or recreational equipment,'' the association said in a written statement. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> held in 1967 that a company could not be required to collect sales taxes on purchases from an out-of-state company unless that company had a retail outlet in the state. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>, for example, collect sales taxes on catalog orders because they have retail stores in every state. But Land's End, the giant mail-order clothing company in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, collects no tax on out-of-state shipments because it has no other outlets. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> and other government organizations are supporting a bill to require large companies to collect tax on shipments to any state in which they regularly solicit business. Thus, if Land's End shipped a catalog to <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, that would be interpreted as soliciting and the company would have to collect the state's sales tax on <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> orders. The bill is sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. It would apply only to the estimated 5 percent of mail-order outlets whose sales exceed $ 12.5 million a year. But those 5 percent account for 70 percent of mail-order sales. Similar legislation stalled last year, and opponents, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, are geared up for the renewed battle. `` If this legislation were to pass, direct marketers would be saddled with tax collection duties for over 7,000 municipal and state tax jurisdictions,'' said <PERSON> Levering </PERSON>. `` That means we can be audited by every one of those jurisdictions, even where our companies do n't have physical presence -LRB- in a state -RRB- and do n't receive benefits. Across the Capitol, at the session sponsored by backers of the bill, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said most mail-order customers charge purchases to their credit cards and so would not have to calculate the sales tax.
