<HEAD>Report Says US Fails to Notify Other Countries on Pesticides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> is failing to notify other countries about dangerous pesticides shipped to them, even though the substances may be used on fruits and vegetables eaten by Americans, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> received repeated warning about such notification more than a decade ago. <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is the biggest market for pesticides, taking 25 percent of world sales, followed by the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, which accounts for 23 percent, according to the report. The fastest growing markets are <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The report quoted the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pesticide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION> as saying about half the pesticides that Latin American countries import are bought from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> furnishes a substantial amount of the fruits and vegetables Americans eat in the winter. `` Not having notices issued could result in continued use in foreign countries of a pesticide that may damage the health of its citizens or damage its environment,'' the report said. `` Additionally, the crops treated with the pesticide could be imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to the detriment of the health of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens and the environment.'' The report, dated April 25, was sent to Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>, chairman of the environment subcommittee in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Government Operations. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> looks into activities of the administration on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Copies were made available to reporters this week. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers had canceled the registration of four pesticides after the agency started or threatened to start special reviews because of dangerous effects on humans or laboratory animals. It found that notices were sent to foreign governments on only one of these pesticides, called cyhexatin, saying it could cause birth defects if pregnant women worked in fields where it was used. No notices were sent on the three others _ <ORGANIZATION> EPN </ORGANIZATION>, captafol and and carbon tetrachloride, according to the office, which quoted <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials as saying that they only send notices when they feel there is a health concern. According to the report, <ORGANIZATION> EPN </ORGANIZATION> damages the nerves of laboratory animals, and captafol gives them tumors and is highly toxic to fish. It said carbon tetrachloride may cause damage to people's livers, lungs, kidneys and nervous systems and is regarded by cancer researchers as a probable cause of cancer In April 1978 the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reported that the agency was not making notifications and therefore not complying with the law. It recommended the agency work out a system with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for telling other countries about dangerous pesticides. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> made another report the following year. `` In the decade since we issued these reports, these problems have not been resolved, though <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has told us that it has made attempts to address them,'' the report said. `` Although publicly acknowledging the need for improvements, the pull of conflicting priorities has generally made it difficult for <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to effect these needed changes, according to officials responsible for the notification program.''
