<HEAD>Forecasts of Economic Slowdown Follow Release of 1989-90 Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires; Dollar amounts U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal budget that critics say does not do enough to tackle inflation and deficit spending has aggravated fears of economic bust after years of sometimes booming growth. Finance Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> is sticking to his view that inflationary pressures can be reduced and that new budget gives the central bank `` the scope to reduce interest rates more quickly than would otherwise be the case.'' However, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>, an Ottawa-based think tank, says in its budget analysis that the risk of recession has grown as a result of the fiscal decisions announced last month. `` We think the economy is going to be very, very soft for the next six months,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, the board's chief economist, told the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> and Mail newspaper. Since a second straight majority government of the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was elected in November, Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and other senior officials have led a steady drumbeat calling for a reduction of government debt. Although the 1989-90 budget raises taxes and cuts federal spending in areas from the military to rail service and child care, it still leaves a deficit of $ 25.6 billion _ up slightly from the previous year's $ 25.2 billion deficit. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> says the new budget is the first step in bringing the annual deficit down to $ 12.6 billion in four years. However, achieving that goal may depend on a drop in interest rates, continued economic growth, and tough tax policies. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasic </PERSON> of the Data Resources forecasting firm says <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> missed the chance to make more progress on the budget deficit at the outset of his second term, when election worries are at their lowest. `` It's a major opportunity that was squandered,'' he said. `` We feel that there's about a 40 percent chance of a recession between now and the end of 1990.'' He said, however, that slower growth is more likely. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jestin </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Scotiabank </ORGANIZATION>, is more optimistic. He predicts growth of 3 percent this year slowing to 2 percent or less in 1990. The Canadian economy has grown, at times dramatically, since the end of the 1982 recession. The gross national product rose beyond inflation by 4 percent in 1987 and 4.5 percent in 1988. Inflation has been running about 4 percent each year, but concern that the economy was overheating prompted <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> governor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> to increase interest rates over the past year to their current 12 percent levels. Forecasts of recession or slowdown have surfaced persistently in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> since the stock market crash of 1987, in large part because of the long expansion.
