<HEAD>Lawmakers Want to Use Drexel Burnham Fine for Drug Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street corruption may provide the windfall the government needs to finance its efforts against illegal drug traffickers, some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> say. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that they are weighing a plan that would channel $ 150 million to be collected in fines from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> this year into federal anti-drug initiatives. Under the proposal, the money would be used to pay for prison improvements, additional law officers, grants to state and local governments and other programs during the last months of fiscal 1989, which ends Sept. 30. The appropriations panel would claim the extra spending is not adding to the federal deficit because it would be financed with the unanticipated fines. `` Thus, in my way of thinking, it's an offset for that spending,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, chairman of the Appropriations justice subcommittee, who proposed the idea. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> agreed last December to pay $ 650 million in fines and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies to settle securities fraud charges brought by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The plan is expected to meet opposition from some Democrats and Republicans who likely will argue that with an potential deficit of more than $ 160 billion this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> fine can hardly be considered unaccounted-for money. In addition, some lawmakers have argued that fines collected by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> should be used to strengthen that agency's law enforcement efforts. The proposal is part of an effort by the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to revamp a $ 4.7 billion domestic spending bill for this year, a measure rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month because ot its high cost. The bill contained money for veterans, college students, anti-drug efforts and other programs. Included in the package was $ 726 million in new spending authority from <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s subcommittee for anti-drug programs, about $ 300 million of which would have actually been spent this year. To make the overall bill more appealing, the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would offset most new spending with cuts in other programs, thus reducing the package's impact on the federal deficit. The Appropriations Committee hopes to bring the new version of the spending bill to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor next week, and <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said he expects the use of the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> money to be included. `` There is a general approval by the members of the committee of this approach, but there is no concrete agreement,'' he said. The chairmen of the 13 Appropriations subcommittees have agreed to drop from the bill $ 250 million for reparations to Japanese-Americans who were held in internment camps during World War II, and most of $ 153 million that would have been used for the homeless. The final package will be less than $ 4.7 billion, but the total will not be determined until the subcommittee chairmen meet again next Tuesday.
