<FIRST>r f PM-RollingRock-Labels     05-11 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rolling Rock-Labels,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rolling Rock Nears Solution to Label Problem ^Eds: also on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The makers of Rolling Rock beer believe they have steered around a bottleneck and are nearing a solution on how to comply with a new law requiring warning labels on beer bottles. The law requires that alcoholic beverage containers carry labels warning of possible adverse health effects from drinking wine, liquor or beer by Nov. 18. But <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Latrobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s distinctive green Rolling Rock bottles carry painted, rather than paper, labels. Therefore, the law would make as many as 1 million cases of <LOCATION> Rolling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> _ each containing 24 bottles of beer _ obsolete because the cost to alter them is prohibitive. The answer may be a grace period during which <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION> would be permitted to print the warning on bottle caps instead of on the containers. `` We're a small player and we do n't want to send out a message that something special is being done for <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Spinelli </PERSON>, vice president of operations, said Wednesday. `` All we're looking for is a time period to phase out the existing bottles as we bring new bottles in,'' he said. `` In the meantime, we've had samples made up with the -LRB- warning -RRB- message on the cap, and it's legible.'' Writing the 41-word warning on the cap would be only a temporary solution. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> specified that the warning must appear on containers and that the print on bottles 12 ounces and larger must be at least two millimeters tall. The law also would affect Rolling Rock's seven-ounce bottles. Rolling Rock has refused to change to a paper label because it feels the painted label gives it its distinctive identity. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON>, D-Pa., has received permission from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to insert language in a spending bill that would grant Rolling Rock a grace period, <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said Wednesday The bill is likely to be considered by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> within a week. It is uncertain how long <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION> might have to fully comply with the law. <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION> has said it could take 10 years before the 24 million bottles wear out, or get broken or lost, although the brewery does not expect to win a grace period nearly that long. On the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> side, <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, the author of the law, has indicated he wants to accommodate <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION> officials if he can, according to aides to Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa. `` Everybody seems to agree this is a unique situation,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said `` Everybody seems agreeable.''
</TEXT>
