<HEAD>Union Preparing For Strike To Protest Mobil's Pullout Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The union representing most black <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said Thursday it is preparing for a strike to protest the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company's refusal to negotiate terms of its planned pullout. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said a strike ballot was planned for next week. If approved, she said, a strike would be launched against <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> and other multinational companies that have not complied with a union demand to negotiate terms favorable to workers in the event of disinvestment from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>, the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company operating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, announced April 28 that it was selling its holdings in the country to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a conglomerate known as <ORGANIZATION> Gencor </ORGANIZATION>, which owns a petroleum company. The sale price was not disclosed, and the ownership change will not take effect until various financial arrangements are completed. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Gencor </ORGANIZATION> had pledged to continue the company's employment policies and honor all existing agreements with the union But union officials nonetheless were angered, saying <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> had rebuffed past attempts to open negotiations by insisting there were no plans for disinvestment. Of <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s 2,800 employees in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, about 1,500 are black, including about 1,200 represented by the chemical workers union. The union had approached several foreign companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>, with a request for certain arrangements in the event of disinvestment. Among the demands were 12-month advance notice, guarentees of job security and full disclosure of the terms of sale. The union has applied to the Industrial Court for an order halting the planned <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> sale. A hearing on the application began Tuesday, but the case was postponed until May 24 and <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> representatives said they would try to provide the union with full information about the pullout. In a related development this week, a syndicate of black and Indian businessmen from <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, site of the main <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> refinery, said they would try to outbid <ORGANIZATION> Gencor </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s assets. A spokesman for the group, <PERSON> Mangalpersaid </PERSON> <PERSON> Hariram </PERSON>, said the businessmen had access to about $ 120 million. Scores of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have withdrawn from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in recent years, citing economic considerations and pressure from the anti-apartheid movement. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said the disinvestment dceision was motivated by `` business considerations,'' including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legislation which has made it more difficult for American companies to make profits in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
