 <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, as anticipated, has announced it is cutting roughly 10 percent of its high-level employees at the textile giant's headquarters. The company said Wednesday 150 employees would be dismissed in an effort to speed decision-making and improve the company's competitiveness following its $ 3 billion acquisition earlier this year by <ORGANIZATION> Farley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. No plant workers will be affected by the restructuring, <PERSON> Pepperrell </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, chairman of Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Farley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, said recently that cost-cutting measures at the corporate headquarters would be coming as soon as possible. Dismissed workers will receive a minimum three months' severance pay and company-paid medical, insurance and other workers' benefits for a year. The restructuring will `` control overhead and remove layers of bureaucracy between decisions and decision-makers, and allow us to move faster in a fast-moving world,'' the company's statement said. `` <PERSON> WestPoint </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepperell </PERSON> will be stronger, leaner and more able to deal with international competition,'' the statement said.
