<HEAD>Superpowers to Cooperate to Fight Oil Spills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> formally pledged Thursday to help each other fight pollution emergencies in northern waters like the oil tanker spill that fouled sections of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s coastline this spring. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> signed the agreement on the last day of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s two-day visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It pledges superpower cooperation in combating spills of oil and other pollutants in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chukchi </LOCATION> seas between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the agreement provides for the development of a `` joint plan of drastic measures'' in the event of a spill. Each country is required to notify the other immediately of a pollution emergency, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials will hold joint exercises on fighting ocean pollution, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The signing of the agreement is a major step toward developing Soviet-American cooperation in dealing with the consequences of ecological disaster at sea,'' <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalimonov </PERSON>, an official in the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. `` The developed mechanism of interaction will allow specialists to define within hours the scope of an accident, map out joint measures to overcome its consequences and get down immediately to their implementation,'' <PERSON> Khalimonov </PERSON> said. `` Earlier such procedures took days and sometimes whole weeks.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the cooperation envisaged by the agreement began to function even before <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> signed the formal document. A Soviet ship designed to skim the surface of the sea was hired to help clean up the oil spilled by an Exxon tanker off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in late March. However, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials, who were paying the Soviets $ 15,000 a day for the aid, said Tuesday the ship was being sent home because it was not designed to handle the hardened, taffylike mass the oil spilled by the tanker has turned into.
