/ORGANIZATION>. But <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION> asked <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> to hold <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> in contempt, claiming <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s maneuvering to try and find a buyer for <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION>, as a way of forcing the American concern out of the litigation, violated <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>'s injunction. <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>, however, declined to find <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> in contempt for the time being. In a two-page order issued early today, <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> said he would entertain another request to hold <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> in contempt of court if it attempted to alter Gold Fields' interest in <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION> so that it could n't vote its shares, which total 49.3 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION> expressed concerns at a hearing Wednesday that if <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> could get a third party to acquire a large stake in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern they could effectively force it to drop the law suit blocking the takeover.
