<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration today proposed rewriting the nation's major jobs training program, which was co-authored by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, to direct most spending to the poor and teen-agers. It also warned states that their programs will have to be improved to receive federal support. `` For years, the government has been distributing money to youth programs in a fragmented and piecemeal fashion, and sometimes without clear expectations of what these youths should achieve,'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on employment and productivity. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and three <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> participants who attended the hearing were meeting with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> this afternoon in a session designed to demonstrate the president's support for the changes. The amendments would significantly change the Job Training Partnership Act created by <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, then a Republican senator from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, and Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said the revisions were necessary because of the changing <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> workforce, not because of any major flaws in the program. `` But <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> can be made even better,'' she told the subcommittee, which has jurisdiction over the act. `` Funds do not always reach the individuals and areas who need help the most. In some communities it is felt that the program does not always result in good jobs and a higher standard of living.'' The changes aim at ending a practice that has prompted criticism of <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> and other training programs, the `` creaming'' of applicants with some marketable skills in order to place them quickly in jobs with little future. They also would also separate youth-training efforts from the various adult programs in which they are now found. And both the state and federal governments would be required to do a far better job coordinating training programs with education, counseling and other services provided by federal, state and local governments. Most of the changes were recommended by an advisory panel named by former <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>. Some also have been suggested by subcommittee members, including the panel's chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> told Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> he was sure that Democrats and Republicans could work out minor differences in their approaches to amending <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> `` I think we're going to get a good bill out of this committee that we're all going to be able to agree on,'' he said. Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, called <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> `` the singularly important work of this committee during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years,'' but said changing work-force demographics made revisions necessary. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> dedicated most of her testimony to how the changes would improve training for teen-agers, something she has said would be among her highest priorities as secretary. She said all youths and half the adults seeking enrollment in <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> programs would need to overcome illiteracy, other basic skills deficiencies or a poor school record. Teen parents and the homeless also would be given preference. And, for the first time, employers who accepted <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> money to help pay for summer jobs for youths would be required to provide some form of approved education or training. The changes, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said, are designed to address projected shortages in the labor force and the related `` skills gap'' exacerbating shortages for jobs in high-tech and other industries. Department officials have said the amendments, if approved, likely would require a modest reduction in the number of people served by <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> made no reference to that in her prepared testimony. The federal government allocated $ 2.4 billion for <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> this year and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has requested stable funding for next year. <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> programs are expected to serve 1.9 million people this year. Because most of the money is spent to support programs administered by state and local agencies, the proposed changes include a number of guidelines those agencies would have to meet before being deemed eligible for <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> funding. At the state and local level, the proposed changes would for the first time require individual assessments of prospective trainees and, for those accepted into the programs, an individually tailored program to meet the distinct education, training and placement needs of each trainee. Removed would be guidelines that encouraged rapid job placement, something <ORGANIZATION> JTPA </ORGANIZATION> critics have said leads to `` creaming'' and placement of trainees in low-skill jobs with few career possibilities. Instead, program administrators would be encouraged to offer more thorough training, with their efforts monitored through a follow-up survey to determine a trainee's progress in the job market.
