<HEAD>Administration Proposes $500 Million Oil Spill Fund</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with proposal for spill cleanup fund in top 12 grafs,
picking up in 5th graf pvs, Skinner said; cuts from end to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration sent legislation to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today calling for a $ 500 million federal oil cleanup fund to be financed by a fee on domestic and imported oil. Officials said the government now has little money earmarked for such an emergency. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> outlined the administration's proposal for a comprehensive oil spill liability and compensation law, saying that in light of the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> spill it is `` imperative to move quickly'' to establish a federal response fund. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauzin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and Navigation, promised that a bill for such a fund would be scheduled for a vote by the panel later this month <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>'s proposal prompted some subcommittee members to note that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has debated, but failed to enact, such a contingency fund for the past 15 years. `` It took a tragedy like the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> to cause the entire <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to focus on the issue,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., who is the sponsor of a bill already under consideration to establish a fund similar to the one proposed by the administration <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said that while the cost of the oil spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> on March 24 has yet to be determined, it could exceed the maximum of $ 500 million envisoned for the proposed cleanup fund Under the legislation proposed by the administration, an oil company or shipper would be liable to up to $ 78 million in cleanup, damage and recovery costs. Costs in excess of that would be covered by the federal fund, which would be collected over the next five years from a 1.3 cent-a-barrel fee on domestic and imported petroleum. When the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> tanker spilled 11 million gallons of oil in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> _ the worst spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history _ a federal oil spill contingency fund had only $ 4 million in it. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> told the congressmen that had the spill been caused by someone with less resources than the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the government would have been left scrambling for money and asking <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for special appropriations. Whatever the price, officials said a day earlier, they doubt <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> can clean the oil from hundreds of miles of rocky <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> coastline by next September as the oil company has said it hopes to do. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that it plans to sharply increase the number of workers assigned to coastal cleanup duties and deploy more barges and boats to the effort. The decision to increase manpower came after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier summer cleanup plans were inadequate But Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> commandant, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing that despite the increased manpower, he considers it `` almost impossible'' for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to clean all the oil from more than 300 miles of shoreline by the Sept. 15 target date. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday that while <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> plans to complete the cleanup this summer, he considers it `` a massive, massive effort ... -LRB- and -RRB- a big challenge'' that might not be possible. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will closely monitor the effort and direct <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> back to work next spring if the cleanup does not meet expectations. Nevertheless, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, told openly skeptical senators the company `` fully expects to clean up'' the beaches by September, after which poor weather would likely make efforts impossible. Confronted by figures showing that only 1.7 miles of the 300 miles of shoreline have been cleaned so far, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said work started slowly because the company tackled the worst beaches first. He promised that even if the September deadline is met, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> will return in the spring to ensure the work is done. The company announced plans to increase the number of cleanup workers from 3,400 to 5,000 this summer after being told by <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> and presidential chief of staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> at a White House meeting Monday that earlier cleanup plans were inadequate. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> also said it would increase the number of barges and boats used in the cleanup, bringing the total to 70 vessels. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, however, expressed doubt in testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the cleanup will be anything short of a long, arduous task. He described how his hands dripped with oil after he reached underneath the gravel on a beach that 200 workers had been cleaning for 10 consecutive days. Increasing the number of cleanup workers will not keep the oil from washing back onto the beaches, <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> told the senators.
