<FIRST>u f AM-LevitatingTrains Bjt   05-11 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Levitating Trains, Bjt,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Recommend High-Tech Trains to Replace Short-Haul Jets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Developing a network of magnetic-levitation trains to replace short-haul aircraft could save the airlines money and reduce airport congestion, some researchers say. Standing in the way of development of the `` maglev'' system is money and a lack of enthusiasm. `` The market for -LRB- maglev trains -RRB- is not well defined,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an economist and director of the <ORGANIZATION> Argonne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, who conducted a yearlong study with five colleagues. `` There is not a constituency that would push the idea.'' In a report soon to be made public, researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> Argonne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> say the costs of building a 2,000-mile network of 300 mph magnetic-levitation trains would be largely offset by multibillion-dollar savings from reducing airline delays, energy costs and airplane acquisition. A maglev network could open gate slots at major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airports to longer domestic and international flights, eliminating the need to build many new airports, the researchers said. Magnetic levitation uses powerful magnets to lift a train above a guideway and propel it at high speeds on a cushion of air. Although the technology exists, there are no maglev trains operating anywhere in the world. Skeptics suggest that a working, short-line demonstration model be built first to prove the feasibility of maglevs. Another obstacle is the high-speed conventional electric train, now in use in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and under development in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sudhir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON>, a professor of engineering and ground transportation at the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> is right about the need to reduce air traffic congestion. But he said a maglev system would be too expensive. `` It would be cheaper than building another airport,'' he said. `` But even less expensive would be high-speed trains,'' which travel at speeds up to 200 mph. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said at speeds of 300 mph and distances up to 600 miles, maglevs could compete economically with aircraft. He said a maglev system linking <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> with cities such as <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> could significantly reduce congestion at the world's busiest airport. `` If you want to expand longer-range domestic and international service at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>, maglev certainly is a way of doing it,'' he said this week. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said more than half the flights arriving or departing daily at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> _ or about 1,100 of a total of 2,000 flights _ cover distances of less than 500 miles. The <ORGANIZATION> Argonne </ORGANIZATION> report estimates that delays and overcrowding at airports cost airlines $ 5 billion a year and that it would cost $ 2 billion to $ 3 billion to build each of the 15 to 20 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airports that experts say are needed to expand the air-transport system into the next century. The maglev system could be built at a cost of $ 15 million a mile, and the cost of the individual vehicles is estimated at $ 2.5 million to $ 5 million each, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Maglevs could be operated on elevated structures built along existing interstate highways to link airports to cities in the region, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. For example, connecting <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> said trains that do n't use magnetic levitation such as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s TGV or <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s ICE offer advantages of cost, compatibility with existing track and the capability of hauling freight. `` High-speed trains are a proven technology, maglevs are not,'' he said, adding that a short line should be constructed to probe maglevs' feasibility. A Japanese firm has proposed constructing a 20-mile maglev line between the airport at <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>. The idea is being considered by <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> officials.
</TEXT>
