<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices closed mostly lower on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Stock Exchange Thursday, in an atmosphere of continued unease about possible labor actions. Despite a strong start, the market was unable to regain its composure after several early selling waves, and prices spent most of the day drifting in a narrow range. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 6.4 points, or 0.3 percent, lower at 2,110.6. The index opened with a gain of 1.3 points, but then quickly dropped to its lowest level, showing a loss of 9.9 points. The market has been plagued in recent weeks by threatened strikes in public transportation, power plants, broadcasting and docks, raising fears of further upward pressure on inflation. Volume fell to 430.5 million shares from 466.6 million on Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index was 4.7 points lower at 1,758.7 at the close. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 500-share index fell 2.84 points to close at 1,196.92.
