<FIRST>s f BC-FutureInvestments Adv14   05-11 1125</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Future Investments, Adv14,1158</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday May 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>What's Left to Invest In? Today's Dreams May Be Tomorrow's Gold Mine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic in AP Access under VENTCAP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> LaVonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Raney </PERSON> took a chance in a fledgling electronics firm she'd read about and bought a few shares at $ 15 each. The time was the early'60s. The company was <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Since then, its stock has shattered the stratosphere, trading lately at around $ 350 a share even after several splits. `` That was my biggest winner. It took three of us around the world twice,'' recalled Mrs. <PERSON> Raney </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, an amateur stock dabbler who has long since cashed her Teledyne treasure. There may not be any <PERSON> Teledynes </PERSON> left in the twilight of the 20th century. But that has n't stopped investors from pouring billions of dollars into what they see as potential gold mines _ startup businesses with products and services ranging from robot cashiers to toxic-waste neutralizers. A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> company, for example, is working on a system that would prevent waste through recycling. Another is trying to perfect chemical-free purified water from industrial sewage. Others see riches in warehouse-like stores of the future that eliminate the middleman or take customer orders via sophisticated computers. `` Hitting it right usually requires a combination of foresight and luck,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sughrue </PERSON>, a researcher at <LOCATION> Needham </LOCATION>, Mass.-based <ORGANIZATION> Venture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which tracks trends in speculative investments. The foresight-luck mix was electronics in the'60s and computers in the 70s. People who foresaw that a company hatched in someone's garage would grow into today's <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, for example, would have multiplied their investment many times over But investing in high-risk businesses is not for the timid. Like the professional poker plays say, do n't bet what you ca n't afford to lose. `` For every Apple ... there are probably 30 to 40 other companies you could lose money on,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feirstein </PERSON>, managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Equitable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's very difficult for an individual investor ... to get in the ground floor of something unless it's an industry he knows.'' Even Mrs. <PERSON> Raney </PERSON>, who profited enormously by beating the crowd on <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>, admits she stumbled into it and prefers to invest in more proven companies. Professional venture capitalists are n't flocking to any particular industry. A report by <ORGANIZATION> Venture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> shows that all the nearly $ 4 billion put in young companies in 1987 _ the latest year for which complete data was available _ was spread out, with no industry getting more than 15 percent. Experts envision growth in specific sectors in communications, consumer products and services, computer hardware and software and medicine, the Venture Economics data shows. Other areas receiving adventurous-investor interest include electronics, industrial products, biotechnology and energy. `` Within each industry there's a narrowly focused niche, and if you hit it right you can make it big,'' said <PERSON> Sughrue </PERSON>. Finding that niche is the hard part. `` We look at probably 500 to 800 business plans a year from people coming to us with ideas,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mumford </PERSON>, managing general partner at <ORGANIZATION> Crosspoint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Altos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` In addition, we go to a lot of trade shows, industry meetings, read literature in a variety of areas and try to forecast where opportunites may be,'' he said. The maturing population of baby boomers, born between 1946 and 1964, are likely to play an important role in what's valuable in the future. <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, editor-in-chief of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Demographics </ORGANIZATION> magazine and author of `` 100 Predictions for the Baby Boom,'' says middle-aged boomers will transform the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into a more conservative, affluent nation, with the home the center of life. Here are a few key growth areas as seen by forward-thinking investment professionals:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Automation</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Severe labor shortages mean machines could replace humans for tasks that range from cashiering to burger flipping to gasoline dispensing. <PERSON> Sughrue </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> Checkrobot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, has developed an automated supermarket checkout system, and <ORGANIZATION> ByVideo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is developing a system that can take retail sales orders. <PERSON> Feirstein </PERSON> says automated bank-teller machine makers such as <ORGANIZATION> Diebold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, also could expand in this field.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Communications</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Networks </ORGANIZATION>, which allow voices, computer data and video signals to be transmitted over the same phone lines through digital signals, are growing rapidly. The underlying technology should make video conferences more common, for example. Giants such as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> are dominating but smaller companies like <ORGANIZATION> Parigain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Torrance </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, could emerge as leaders, said <PERSON> Mumford </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Computers</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Predictions are tough because technology cycles shift quickly. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajarin </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said the trend today is toward smaller computers with greater capabilities and bigger memories. <ORGANIZATION> Prairietek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, is an example of a little-known company working in this area, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Health Care</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation is growing so rapidly in health care that many corporate planners are aggressively seeking ways to cut costs. Look for an emergence in mail order prescriptions from pharmaceutical giants such as <ORGANIZATION> Baxter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Feirstein </PERSON> said. Specialized treatment may also become more prevalent. <PERSON> Mumford </PERSON> said he's backing a <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, company known as <ORGANIZATION> NeuroCare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, developing non-hospital rehabilitation for patients who've suffered head injuries. Biotechnology treatments for afflictions ranging from cancer to AIDS should become more common in the middle to late 1990s, many experts say. `` They're taking a lot of the things developed over the past 10 years and now using them both for disease treatment and diagnostics,'' said <PERSON> Mumford </PERSON>. Poised for possible growth, experts say, are companies like <ORGANIZATION> Biosurface </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, which is developing synthetic skin. This area is especially risky. San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s stock skyrocketed before slumping on slower-than-expected sales of its blood clot dissolving drug, TPA.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Retail</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mumford </PERSON> says tomorrow's consumers will want exceptionally cheap prices, superior services or both. He and others see an emergence in warehouse distributors that cut prices by selling directly to customers. `` Investments in that area nearly doubled from'86 to'87,'' said <PERSON> Sughrue </PERSON>. Staples, a <LOCATION> Newton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, retailer that sells bargain office supplies warehouse-style, is already becoming popular.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Waste Management</NOTE>
<TEXT>
