<HEAD>Dollar Firm In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strong demand in the absence of central bank intervention drove the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar higher against the major currencies in European trading on Thursday. Gold prices also rose after dipping in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Dealers said the news that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retail sales in April rose by a lower than expected 0.4 percent failed to shake confidence in the American currency. One <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealer said the day's performance confirmed the underlying demand for dollars and the market's reluctance to sell them. The central banks again made no effort at a concerted intervention to bring the dollar's exchange rate down by selling dollars, although dealers said they can be expected to enter the market if the dollar rises much above 1.92 West German marks. The dealers said the absence of intervention suggests that the central banks tacitly acknowledged their sales of dollars had been unable to bring the exchange rate down. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6655 late Thursday, cheaper for buyers than Wednesday's late $ 1.6717. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Wednesday's late rates: 1.9135 West German marks, up from 1.9047; 1.7060 Swiss francs, up from 1.6925; 6.4665 French francs, up from 6.4645; 2.1580 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1500; 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from 1,390.125; 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849. Gold bullion prices improved slightly in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Gold traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major market, at a bid price of $ 379.00 a troy ounce, up from $ 377.25. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 378.20, up from $ 376.75. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at $ 377.25, down from $ 378.25. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 5.66 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.68.
