ine might be a lucrative addition. <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> finds <PERSON> Avon </PERSON> an attractive takeover prospect partly because ownerhip of <PERSON> Avon </PERSON> would open the door to markets <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> has been trying to enter. `` Avon is well established in some international markets that'd we'd love to get into,'' he said, naming <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> as examples Latin American countries have sufficient incomes to support significant growth in their direct sales markets. So far, <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> is operating only in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> also was motivated to pursue <PERSON> Avon </PERSON> by the opportunity to turn <PERSON> Avon </PERSON>'s sales representatives into distributors of a wider array of products. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>, a privately held company based in <LOCATION> Ada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, has about 1 million distributors around the world selling <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> household, personal care and environmental products. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> distributors also sell <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> computer gear, <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> services, office coffee making equipment and other brand name products. <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Avon </PERSON> has failed so far to capitalize on its cosmetics business and broaden it into a full health and beauty aids operation. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>'s cosmetic interests represent only a small portion of the company's operations so an acquisition of <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION> would cause little duplication. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 39-a-share takeover proposal places a value of about $ 2.1 billion on the company based on nearly 54 million outstanding Avon common shares. <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> also would have to acquire 18 million preferred shares which could be converted into common in the event of a takeover, adding about $ 700 million to the price. Speculators on Wall Street have indicated they believe that a higher bid may be forthcoming. Avon shares closed at $ 39.50, off 37 -LCB- cents, in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Thursday, after gaining $ 3.87 -LCB- on Wednesday. Avon Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> has said repeatedly the company is not for sale but has said <PERSON> Avon </PERSON>'s board would give <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>'s offer consideration. To bolster its defense against <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Avon </PERSON> has sued <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> and its investment partner <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>. The partnership has said they own about 10.3 percent of <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION> common stock. <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> investor, is not involved in <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>'s takeover offer But in its <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filing, <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> may `` explore the possibility of purchasing'' some of <PERSON> Avon </PERSON>'s assets if the takeover succeeds but `` no agreement, arrangement or understanding has been reached.'' Avon spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said the company had no comment on information in <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION>'s filing. <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amway </ORGANIZATION> is awaiting a response from <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION>. `` We believe that the board will invite us in for discussion and we're waiting for that invitation,'' <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> said.
