<HEAD>House Approves Minimum Wage Bill; Both Sides Mull Post-Veto Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf with Mrs. Dole reax after 5th graf pvs, There
is ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to raise the minimum wage to $ 4.55 an hour by October 1991, leaving only a final <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote before the bill goes to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has promised to veto it. In the first major domestic policy dispute of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, neither house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has backed down despite <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s insistence that the minimum should be raised only to $ 4.25 by January 1992 _ and then only if the proposal allows employers to pay a lower `` training wage'' to new workers for six months. The minimum is now $ 3.35, where it has been since 1981. The only congressional action still required is a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote on the bill drafted by <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators, and that could come as early as next week. There is virtually no doubt that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will follow through on his promise to veto the measure and the 247-172 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote for passage suggested the Democrats remain short of the two-thirds majority it would need to override the president. `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> insisted on sending President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a bill that would cost hundreds of thousands of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> their opportunity to work _ a bill he most certainly will veto,'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote. Still, Democratic leaders in both chambers have promised to attempt an override. In the meantime, Democrats hope to bring public pressure on the White House by characterizing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s position as unfair to the working poor and by juxtaposing his veto threat with his plan to spend billions of dollars to rescue troubled savings and loans and his proposal to lower capital gains tax rates. `` The wealthiest of the wealthy would get tax breaks big enough to hire two minimum wage workers each to take care of their gardens or do their laundry,'' said Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>. `` Is this the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> full employment program? Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the `` meager increase'' included in the legislation still would leave the minimum wage trailing inflation increases since the wage floor last was raised. `` Today we seek to provide fairness for the working poor of this country,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. `` There are at least 4 million of them who receive no more than the minimum wage.'' Republicans, however, said Democrats were passing up an opportunity to increase the minimum wage by accepting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s more modest offer and instead had decided on waging a political battle with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for control of the domestic-policy agenda. The Republicans also reiterated their contention that raising the minimum wage without also establishing a six-month subminimum for newly hired workers would trigger massive job losses. `` The bottom line is it will cost at least 650,000 new jobs in three years, the very people that we want to bring into the workforce to help them become productive members of society,'' Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, said of the bill passed Thursday. `` There can be no further compromise that throws people out of work. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has offered the compromise.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had proposed raising the minumum wage to $ 4.25 an hour by January 1992 provided employers could pay new hires the `` training wage'' for six months. In rejecting that offer, Democratic leaders said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed increase was too small and also assailed his `` training wage'' because the provision requires no actual training. In their final bill, Democrats allowed workers with less than 60 days of work experience to be paid a subminimum. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, much like the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, sponsors have more than enough votes to gain passage of the measure but seem short of the two-thirds majority needed to override a veto. `` If he vetoes it, then he has declared the end of the honeymoon,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, D-Pa. The result of a veto, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, will be action on a lengthy list of Democrat-sponsored bills dealing with such issues as parental leave, child care and mandatory health insurance. `` A veto would tell other members there is no reason to say the president is trying to get along,'' said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` That would undoubtedly cause the sponsors of those bills to demand that they advance.'' But administration aides have said one of the reasons <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will veto the minimum-wage bill is to assert his position on domestic policy to prevent the Democrats' agenda from gaining momentum. Business and labor groups plan media campaigns and other lobbying efforts to pressure lawmakers considered to be potential swing votes in an attempted veto override. Proponents of the bill also are trying to draft another minimum wage bill for quick consideration should they lose the veto fight, which appears likely.
</TEXT>
