<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained value against most major currencies Thursday despite further evidence of a slowdown in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic growth. Gold prices rose, partly in response to the tension in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Foreign-exchange dealers said demand for dollars appeared unaffected by a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that retail sales rose by only 0.4 percent in April. Economists said the weak sales figure showed the extent to which higher interest rates and inflation are discouraging consumer spending. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalzer </PERSON>, an assistant vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Amsterdam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rotterdam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said there was no indication that central banks intervened in the currency markets to influence exchange rates. `` Until we get some concerted intervention, where they really mean business, the dollar will continue to go up,'' she said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6655 late Thursday, cheaper for buyers than late Wednesday's $ 1.6717. Sterling weakened against the dollar in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, ending the day at $ 1.6645 compared with $ 1.6740 on Wednesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with Wednesday's late rates included: 1.9160 West German marks, up from 1.9020; 135.37 Japanese yen, up from 134.41; 1.7080 Swiss francs, up from 1.6921; 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1843; 6.4755 French francs, up from 6.4220; and 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from 1,385.25 Late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Wednesday's late rates: 1.9135 West German marks, up from 1.9047; 1.7060 Swiss francs, up from 1.6925; 6.4665 French francs, up from 6.4645; 2.1580 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1500; 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from 1,390.125; and 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849 Gold prices were bid higher as traders considered the implications of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to send combat troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Frequently during times of political unrest or other uncertainty, investors buy gold as a safe haven for their money. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was sending 2,000 combat troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and evacuating <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependents to protect Americans from the violence that started after the country's presidential elections. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 379.40 for a troy ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, up from late Wednesday's bid of $ 376.60 Earlier gold bullion for current delivery rose $ 3.30 a troy ounce to $ 381 on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold bullion prices improved slightly in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Gold traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major market, at a bid price of $ 379.00 a troy ounce, up from $ 377.25. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, was $ 378.20, up from $ 376.75. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at $ 377.25, down from $ 378.25. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled at $ 5.65 a troy ounce, up from $ 5.607 Wednesday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 5.66 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.68.
