<HEAD>Bill Would Give Feds Power to Block Northwest Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation giving the secretary of transportation the power to block buyouts of airlines if a transaction would imperil flying safety was introduced Thursday by Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>'s bill would bar any acquisition that would give the airline an even ratio of debt to equity unless the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, after a full review, found the airline could function properly after the takeover and that the transaction would n't harm the public interest. The <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Democrat </PERSON> said his bill was prompted by the recent offer for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> by billionaire oilman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` This is not an effort to shield inept management from market forces,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. The legislation was intended rather to shield the public from `` high-stakes billionaires who would play monopoly'' with the nation's air transportation system, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in ruling whether a takeover could proceed, would under <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>'s bill be required to consider the financial fitness of the new owner, the likelihood that the purchaser would comply with federal aviation laws and the `` managerial competence'' of the purchaser. If passed, the legislation would be retroactive to the beginning of this year. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said he knew of no transactions so far concluded that would be affected by the bill. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline industry has been largely free from federal regulation since 1978, although a takeover must comply with federal antitrust laws. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> argued that safety considerations mean corporate takeovers of airlines deserve special treatment. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> has offered $ 2.7 billion, or $ 90 a share, to buy <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, is the nation's fourth-largest airline Corporate takeovers are often financed by the issuance of high-yield `` junk'' bonds paid off through the sale of corporate assets or stringent cost-cutting. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> argued that reduced maintenance was one area where a debt-ridden airline could cut expenditures, thereby imperiling the safety of the flying public.
