<HEAD>SEC Censures Chicago Options Exchange</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of exchange in lead.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, in a rare action, censured the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday, accusing the board of failing to enforce its own rules on trading manipulation. The <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>, the largest options exchange in the world, accepted the censure without admitting or denying the government's allegations It is only the third time in 10 years that the federal commission has censured one of the exchanges it regulates. The commission said that in 1986 the exchange's <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> ignored compelling circumstantial evidence in failing to initiate disciplinary action against 12 market makers, including a former <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> vice chairman, and seven affiliated firms. The agency and the exchange refused to identify the individuals or their firms. However, an exchange source who spoke only on condition of anonymity identified one of the 12 as <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahey </PERSON>, who was <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> vice chairman at the time of the alleged misconduct in 1985. The 12 individuals and their firms were accused of a practice known as `` chumming'' _ that is, they arranged to trade options among themselves primarily for the purpose of creating an artificial appearance of activity. As part of the settlement with the exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> agreed not to pursue action against the individuals and firms involved, according to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, an attorney in the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office. The government is also requiring the exchange to increase its surveillance of trading and to periodically inform its members about its rules prohibiting trading done to artificially influence price or volume. The options involved included a number of over-the-counter stocks and options on the Standard and Poor's 250, which tracks 250 over-the-counter industrial stocks. The options were listed on several exchanges, so, falsely pumping up activity on the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchange could attract more business to it and away from the others. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Moulds </PERSON>, a spokesman for the exchange, declined to answer questions, but he read a statement, which said, in part: `` In the interest of closing out an old matter, the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> voluntarily agreed to the entry of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> order. ... The exchange had already completed all undertakings called for in the order prior to the order being entered.''
