<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, dollar quotes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar hit an eight-month high against the Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> were sharply lower. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 89.14-point gainer Thursday, ended the morning session at 33,839.36 points, down 242.13 points, or 0.7 percent. After opening at 135.40 yen, up 0.85 yen from Thursday's close of 134.55 yen, the dollar moved in a range of 135.40 -.65 yen The currency was being traded at 135.48 yen at midday. It was the first time that the dollar traded at the 135.65 level since Sept. 6. Traders said the dollar's surge followed overnight gains against most major currencies, including the Japanese yen, on overseas markets. The dollar's rise was triggered by a decision Thursday by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to send more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to help protect the 51,000 American civilians living in that country, said a trader at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke anonymously. There are 10,000 troops already based at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> installations along the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency is regarded as a safe haven in times of international tension. In a press confernce Friday morning, Finance Minister <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maruyama </PERSON> said he was not alarmed by the dollar's surge. `` The dollar was bought due partly to its -LRB- potential -RRB- strength at the time of an emergency such as confusion,'' over the Panamanian presidential election, <PERSON> Maruyama </PERSON> said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZ